u8fd0\u91cf\u603b\u7ed3></ref>\n| track_gauge = {{Track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| reporting marks = \n| operator = Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd.\n| owner = Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd.\n| website = {{url|www.wuhanrt.com|www.wuhanrt.com}}\n| map = [[File:Route Map of Wuhan Metro.svg|300px]]\n| alt = \n| head_office =77 Huanle Avenue, Hongshan District, Wuhan\n| caption = \n| area served = \n| line_number = \n| start = \n| headway =2.5 - 9 min\n| end = \n| chief_executive = \n| character = Elevated and underground\n| map_state = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s2=\u6b66\u6c49\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\n|t2=\u6b66\u6f22\u8ecc\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\n|p2=W\u01d4h\u00e0n Gu\u01d0d\u00e0o Ji\u0101ot\u014dng\n|s=\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\n|t=\u6b66\u6f22\u5730\u9435\n|p=W\u01d4h\u00e0n D\u00ecti\u011b\n|order=st\n}}\nThe '''Wuhan Metro''' is a [[rapid transit]] system serving the city of [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China, owned and operated by Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd. \nThe system began operation on July 28, 2004 with the completion of a ten-station long elevated line between [[Huangpu Road Station|Huangpu Road]] and [[Zongguan Station|Zongguan]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ctdsb.cnhubei.com/html/ctdsb/20110409/ctdsb1348512.html |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f7b\u8f68\u4eca\u8fce\u7b2c1\u4ebf\u540d\u4e58\u5ba2 |script-work=zh:\u8346\u695a\u7f51-\u695a\u5929\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5 |language=Chinese |date=April 9, 2011}}</ref> making Wuhan the sixth city in [[mainland China]] to have a metro system after [[Beijing Subway|Beijing]], [[Tianjin Metro|Tianjin]], [[Shanghai Metro|Shanghai]], [[Guangzhou Metro|Guangzhou]] and [[Dalian Metro|Dalian]].<ref>[http://urbanrail.net/as/wuha/wuhan.htm Wuhan], ''UrbanRail.net''</ref> Line 1 is the first metro line in China to have been wrongly referred to as a light rail ({{zh|labels=no |s=\u8f7b\u8f68 |p=q\u012bng gu\u01d0}}) system in Chinese terminology.<ref>Wuhan, along with other three Chinese cities, has been the first batch to be approved to build so-called \"light rail\" system in China since 2000, see {{cite web |url=http://news.huochepiao.com/2012-7/20127177020183.htm |script-title=zh:2000\u5e74\uff0c\u56fd\u5bb6\u6279\u51c6\u957f\u6625\u3001\u5927\u8fde\u3001\u6b66\u6c49\u548c\u91cd\u5e864\u4e2a\u57ce\u5e02\u4e3a\u9996\u6279\u8f7b\u8f68\u5efa\u8bbe\u793a\u8303\u57ce\u5e02}}. However, [[Changchun]] built a true light-rail system, [[Dalian]] built a metro-style commuter rail system (and is referred to as {{zh|s=\u5feb\u8f68 |p=ku\u00e0i gu\u01d0}}, not {{zh|links=no |s=\u8f7b\u8f68 |p=q\u012bng gu\u01d0}}), and [[Chongqing]] opted for a monorail system, whereas Wuhan was the only one to build an elevated metro system. See [http://urbanrail.net/as/wuha/wuhan.htm \"Urbanrail--Wuhan\"] and affiliated Wikipedia pages. See also a comment from He Jibin, an Urban Planning official from Wuhan Municipality: \"{{lang|zh-Hans|\u4e0d\u8981\u8ba4\u4e3a\u5730\u4e0b\u7684\u624d\u662f\u5730\u94c1\uff0c1\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e5f\u662f\u5730\u94c1\u7684\u4e00\u79cd\u65b9\u5f0f...\u4f55\u7ee7\u658c\u5f00\u95e8\u89c1\u5c71\u5730\u7ea0\u6b63\u6982\u5ff5\uff0c\u4ed6\u662f\u6b66\u6c49\u5e02\u56fd\u571f\u89c4\u5212\u5c40\u4ea4\u901a\u5e02\u653f\u5904\u5904\u957f\u2026\u2026}}\" {{cite journal | url=http://dawuhan.cnhubei.com/ |script-title=zh:\u90a3\u4e9b\u5e74\uff0c\u6211\u4eec\u4e00\u8d77\u8ffd\u7684\u5730\u94c1 | author=Li Fei (\u674e\u6590) |script-journal=zh:\u5927\u6b66\u6c49 |date=March 2012 | volume=148 | page=33}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019|November}}, there are 9 lines in operation, totaling 228 stations and {{Convert|339|km|mi}} of system length.<ref name=Wuhan8-3 />\n\nWuhan Metro is pursuing ambitious expansion projects to connect Wuhan's three boroughs, divided by the [[Yangtze River]] and [[Han River (Hubei)|Han River]], to accommodate increasing inter-borough traffic and provide commuter services to suburban [[Satellite city|satellite cities]]. Its future expansion includes the operation of 12 urban lines and 13 suburban lines, totaling a length of {{convert|1045|km|mi}}, making it one of the most expansive rail transit systems in the world. As of 2017, there are currently 13 subway expansion projects totaling {{convert|304|km|abbr=on}} of subway being constructed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://m.xinhuanet.com/hb/2018-10/01/c_1123512458.htm |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf11\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a \u957f\u6c5f\u516c\u94c1\u96a7\u9053\u540c\u65f6\u542f\u7528|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Impact of 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on Wuhan Metro==\nOn 23 January 2020, the entire metro network was shut down, along with all other public transport in the city, including national railway and air travel, to halt the spread of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Hubei]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/01/22/798602296/public-transport-in-wuhan-suspended-due-to-coronavirus-concerns|title=Public Transport In Wuhan Suspended Due To Coronavirus Concerns|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51215348|title=Virus-hit Chinese city shuts public transport|date=2020-01-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nOn 28 March 2020, six lines (Line 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7) resumed operation, after two-month [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|lockdown]]. Line 8, Line 11, and Yangluo Line remain out of service.<ref name=\"resume\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/25/c_138914547.htm|title=Wuhan buses hit the road after two-month lockdown|website=Xinhua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn {{date|2020-4-8}}, Line 8 Phase 1 resumed operation. Line 8 Phase 3, Line 11 and Yangluo Line remain suspended.<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.chinanews.com/gn/2020/04-07/9150068.shtml|title =\u6b66\u6c49\uff1a4\u67088\u65e5\u8d77\u6062\u590d\u51fa\u79df\u8f66\u8fd0\u8425 \u9002\u65f6\u6062\u590d\u7f51\u7ea6\u8f66\u8fd0\u8425|author =Huang Lei\uff1bWang Yang|date =2020-04-07 |publisher =Hubei Daily}}</ref>\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|footer=\n|lines=2\n|width=160\n|height=120\n|align=center\n|File:Wuhan Metro requests passengers to wear masks throughout their journeys during COVID-19 pandemic.jpg|Wuhan Metro requests passengers to wear masks throughout their journeys during COVID-19 pandemic\n|File:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf\u8f66\u53a2\u5185\u4fdd\u6301\u793e\u4ea4\u8ddd\u79bb\u7684\u63d0\u793a.jpg|Notices in the carriage of Line 7 to remind people to maintain social distancing\n|FILE:Observation area in Xunlimen Station, Wuhan Metro Line 1.jpg|Observation area for potential COVID-19 patients in Xunlimen Station, Line 1\n|FILE:Self-service disinfection area & body temperature measurement area in Garden Expo North Station.jpg|Self-service disinfection area & body temperature measurement area in Garden Expo North Station.jpg\n}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Wuhan_Metro_Timelapse2019.gif|thumb|400px|Evolution of the Wuhan Metro]]\n\nPreliminary studies of urban rail transit system were prompted by the city shortly after a [[National Railway Company of Belgium|Belgian Railways]] delegation visit in 1984. Following the demolition of old [[Beijing-Hankou Railway]], the city of [[Wuhan]] planned to utilize the corridor to construct the city's first rapid transit rail line. In September 1992, the [[Wuhan Metro Construction Group]] was established by [[Wuhan Municipal Construction Commission]] and a supervision group, led by the mayor [[Qian Yunlu]], was subsequently formed in 1993 to facilitate the project's funding, planning, logistics, and organization. Yet, it was seven years before the city was able to fund construction.\n\nIn October 1999, the [[National Development and Reform Commission|National Planning Commission]] (predecessor of the National Development and Reform Commission) approved the Wuhan \"Light Rail\" project (Line 1, phase 1), signaling the start of serious work on the rail transit project. On October 2, 2000, the [[Wuhan|Wuhan Municipal Government]] ratified the establishment of the [[Wuhan Rail Transit Co., Ltd]]., and contracted construction, operation, administration and related real estate development to the corporation.\n\nIn December 2000, the National Planning Commission accepted a feasibility report on the project and approved construction on phase 1 of Line 1. On December 23, 2000, the project broke ground and comprehensive construction began.\n\nIn 2002, with the anticipation of an economic boom and increasing demand for urban rail transit, Wuhan Municipal Government approved the city's first long-term rail transit master plan. On July 28, 2004, the ten-station long \"light rail\" line was opened to the public and entered revenue service in August. However, low ridership discouraged the city from funding the extension project, for which ground had been broken on December 15, 2005, and a 4-year delay in construction ensued. In April, 2006, the [[National Development and Reform Commission|NDRC]] ratified a six-year construction/operation plan, but it was not until a year later on April 9, 2007 that NDRC accepted the feasibility report for line 1, phase 2 (the extension project) and approved construction on the project.\n\nIn the interim, construction began on the [[Fanhu station]] of the fully underground line 2 on November 16, 2006, as a response to the six-year plan adopted by NDRC earlier. Construction also began on the underground line 4 stations of [[Wuchang railway station]] in June, and [[Wuhan railway station]] in September, as parts of the integral capital project to revamp and construct the [[Wuhan Railway Hub System|Wuhan Railway Hub]].\n\nIn May 2007, the [[Hubei Provincial Development and Reform Commission]] (HDRC) approved preliminary designs on the Line 1, phase 2, and comprehensive construction subsequently commenced in June. On May 15, the city government approved the establishment of [[Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd]]., which would replace the [[Wuhan Rail Transit Co., Ltd]] and assume its responsibilities and benefits.\n\nOn September 12, 2007, the NDRC accepted the feasibility report to Line 2, phase 1, and preliminary designs were approved by the HDRC in December 2007. However, it was not until September 2008 that land purchases and funding were facilitated and comprehensive construction began to take place. In October 2009, drilling of the [[Yangtze River]] tunnel started.\n\nOn March 13, 2009, the NDRC accepted feasibility report to Line 4, phase 1. On May 13, 2009, the HDRC ratified preliminary designs on Line 4, phase 1. Comprehensive construction ensued on the [[Wuchang District|Wuchang]] segment of Line 4. A more ambitious urban rapid transit plan was submitted for NDRC review in October, 2009, and in late November, on-site panel investigations were conducted by [[China International Engineering Consulting Corporation]].\n\nIn February 2010 (Wuhan Metro)'s first commercial property topped out in [[Hanxi 1st Road station]]. On July 29, Line 1 phase 2 entered revenue service from [[Dijiao station|Dijiao]] to [[Dongwu Boulevard station|Dongwu Boulevard]]. Despite plans to extend the westernmost terminus to [[Jinshan Avenue]] in [[Dongxihu District]], the station was never built. A short stub with crossover tracks was constructed behind Dongwu Boulevard. [[Zhuyehai]], a station in [[Qiaokou District]], remained non-operational in spite of the existence of complete platforms. Neither exits nor staircases had been built yet. It was due to open when the Wuhan [[IKEA]] store was completed in late 2014.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u8f7b\u8f68\u4e8c\u671f\u589e\u8bbe\u7af9\u53f6\u6d77\u7ad9 |url=http://hb.qq.com/a/20090531/000131.htm |language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nA revised and more detailed construction plan was accepted by the NDRC on January 31, 2011. The plan specified the city's plan to complete construction on Line 3, 4, 6, 7 and 8 before 2017. Beginning on March 1, Line 1 subdivided its fare zones from 3 to 5 and lowered maximum fare from 5 CNY / ride to 4 CNY / ride. [[Wuhan Tong]] cardholders will receive a 20 percent discount on single ride fares.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f7b\u8f68\u7968\u4ef7\u4e0b\u8c03 |url=http://www.hb.xinhuanet.com/newscenter/2011-03/03/content_22188105.htm |language=Chinese}}</ref> On April 9, Line 1 welcomed its 100,000,000th customer, who was awarded a one-year pass to the Metro.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f7b\u8f68\u5ba2\u6d41\u91cf\u4eca\u65e5\u7a81\u78341\u4ebf |url=http://news.cnxianzai.com/2011/04/324488.html |language=Chinese}}</ref> On September 9, preliminary designs on Line 4, phase 2 ([[Hanyang District|Hanyang]] segment) was approved by HDRC.\n\nOn February 17, 2012, the NDRC accepted a feasibility report on line 3, phase 1, the fourth line in Wuhan Metro's grid and the first to cross the [[Han River (Yangtze River tributary)|Han River]], connecting the boroughs of [[Hankou]] and [[Hanyang District|Hanyang]]. A feasibility report to Line 6\u2014the second Hankou-Hanyang connection\u2014was also approved by the NDRC on December 21, 2012. Seven days later, line 2 entered revenue service, connecting some of the most populated areas of Hankou, Wuchang, and the [[Optics Valley of China|Optics Valley]].\n\nOn April 12, 2013, the NDRC granted acceptance to a feasibility report of Line 8, phase 1, which connects Hankou and Wuchang via the [[Second Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge|Second Yangtze River Bridge]] corridor. Construction began in June 2013 and was completed in December 2017.\n\n===Timeline of service expansion===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Segment description\n!Date opened\n!Station(s)\n!# of new stations\n!Length (km)\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 1\n|{{date|2004-7-28}}\n|Zongguan \u2014 Huangpu Road\n|10{{NoteTag|in which Taipingyang Station was postponed to open on {{date|2006-4-8}}.}}\n|9.769\n|-\n|Phase \u2161 of Line 1\n|{{date|2010-7-29}}\n| Dongwu Boulevard \u2014 Zongguan;<br> Huangpu Road \u2014 Dijiao\n|16{{NoteTag|in which Zhuyehai Station was postponed to open on {{date|2014-9-17}}.<ref>[http://qzgh.qiaokou.gov.cn/qkxw/bmdt/201409/t20140917_139172.shtml \u8f7b\u8f68\u7af9\u53f6\u6d77\u7ad9\u5b9c\u5bb6\u8054\u5eca\u6865\u6295\u5165\u4f7f\u7528 (Zhuyehai station opened)]</ref>}}\n|18.494\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 2\n|{{date|2012-12-28}}\n| Jinyintan \u2014 Optics Valley Square\n|21\n|27.152\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 4<ref>[http://cjweek.cjn.cn/html/2013-12/27/content_5269051.htm Section one of Metro Line 4 opens]</ref>\n|{{date|2013-12-28}}\n| Wuchang Railway Station \u2014 Wuhan Railway Station\n|15\n|17.974\n|-\n|Hankou North extension of Line 1\n|{{date|2014-5-28}}\n|  Dijiao \u2014 Hankou North\n|3\n|5.555 \n|-\n|Phase \u2161 of Line 4\n|{{date|2014-12-28}}\n| Huangjinkou \u2014 Wuchang Railway Station\n|13\n|15.429\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 3<ref name=\"Line 3\">{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5373\u5c06\u5730\u94c1\u6210\u73af \"\u73af\u91d1\u65f6\u4ee3\"\u91cd\u6784\u5546\u4e1a\u5730\u7406  |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/house/wh/2015-12/24/c_1117562445.htm |work=\u957f\u6c5f\u65e5\u62a5 |language=Chinese |date=2015-12-24 |accessdate=2015-12-24 }}</ref>\n|{{date|2015-12-28}}\n|Zhuanyang Boulevard \u2014 Hongtu Boulevard\t\n|24\n|29.660\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 6\n| rowspan=\"2\"|{{date|2016-12-28}}<ref name=\"\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u673a\u573a\u7ebf\u53ca6\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a \u6e56\u5317\u79fb\u52a8\u5168\u9762\u5e03\u5c40\u7f51\u7edc\u8986\u76d6\">[http://tech.cnr.cn/techgd/20161228/t20161228_523405232.shtml  \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u673a\u573a\u7ebf\u53ca6\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a \u6e56\u5317\u79fb\u52a8\u5168\u9762\u5e03\u5c40\u7f51\u7edc\u8986\u76d6]</ref>\n|Jinyinhu Park \u2014 Dongfeng Motor Corporation\t\n|27\n|35.512\n|-\n|Northern extension of Line 2{{NoteTag|also known as Airport Line }}\n|Tianhe International Airport \u2014 Jinyintan\t\n|7\n|19.957\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 8\n| rowspan=\"3\"|{{date|2017-12-26}}\n|Jintan Road \u2014 Liyuan\t\n|12\n|16.204\n|-\n|Yangluo Line\n|Houhu Boulevard \u2014 Jintai\n|16\n|34.575\n|-\n|Jinghe extension of Line 1\n|Dongwu Boulevard \u2014 Jinghe\n|3\n|4.118\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 7\n| rowspan=\"2\"|{{date|2018-10-1}}<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://hb.qq.com/a/20181001/003195.htm#p=1|website=www.xinhuanet.com|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u957f\u6c5f\u516c\u94c1\u96a7\u9053\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a 7\u53f7\u7ebf\u300111\u53f7\u7ebf\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425|access-date=2017-12-26}}</ref>\n|Garden Expo North \u2014 Yezhihu\n|19\n|30.413\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 11\n|Optics Valley Railway Station \u2014 Zuoling\n|13\n|18.744\n|-\n|Southern extension of Line 7\n|{{date|2018-12-28}}\n|Yezhihu \u2014 Qinglongshan Ditiexiaozhen\n|7\n|16.550\n|-\n|Southern extension of Line 2\n|{{date|2019-2-19}}\n|Optics Valley Square \u2014 Fozuling\n|10\n|13.195\n|-\n|Wsetern extension of Line 4<ref name=cjn201909>{{cite web|url=http://news.cjn.cn/sywh/201909/t3460424.htm|title=\u5b9a\u4e86\uff01\u5730\u94c1\u8521\u7538\u7ebf25\u65e5\u4e0a\u53489\u65f6\u5f00\u901a|date=2019-09-23}}</ref>\n|{{date|2019-9-25}}\n|Bailin \u2014 Huangjinkou\n|9\n|16.288\n|-\n|Phase \u2162 of Line 8<ref name=Wuhan8-3>{{cite web|url=https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/3LnB6Rl_lBp71IWU5fBITA|title=\u660e\u65e59\u70b9\uff0c\u6b66\u6c49\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a8\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e09\u671f\u5de5\u7a0b\u5f00\u901a\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425|work=Wuhan Metro Operation|date=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n|{{date|2019-11-6}}\n|Yezhihu \u2014 Military Athletes' Village\n|3\n|4.832\n|}\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n==Lines==\n{{center|[[File:Wuhan Metro System Map.svg|750px]]}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;text-align:center\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" colspan=\"100\" style=\"width:450px; \"|Current system\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Line Name\n! class=\"unsortable\" colspan=\"2\"|Termini\n! Opened\n! Last extension\n! | Length<ref name=\u7968\u52a1\u89c4\u5b9a>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wuhanrt.com/public_forward.aspx??url=public_content_page.aspx?newid=5668a9d3-2609-4318-86dd-7b4d438be0e5&dtag=menu_motion_1|title =Ticketing regulations |publisher =Wuhan Metro Group Co., Ltd.|date =2019-11-05}}</ref>\n! | Stations\n! | Layout\n|- \n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|1}}\" | '''[[Line 1 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 1</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"|{{ill|Jinghe Station|lt=Jinghe|zh|\u5f84\u6cb3\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"|{{stl|WHM|Hankou North}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2004-07-28}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{date|2017-12-26}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{convert|37.936|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 32\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Elevated\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|2}}\" | '''[[Line 2 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 2</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{stl|WHM|Tianhe International Airport}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Fozuling Station|lt=Fozuling|zh|\u4f5b\u7956\u5cad\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2012-12-28}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2019-2-19}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|60.304|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 38\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Elevated & underground\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|3}}\" | '''[[Line 3 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 3</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{stl|WHM|Zhuanyang Boulevard}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{stl|WHM|Hongtu Boulevard}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2015-12-28}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|29.660|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|- \n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|4}}\" | '''[[Line 4 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 4</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Bailin Station|lt=Bailin|zh|\u67cf\u6797\u7ad9 (\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1)}}<ref name=sina1004>{{cite web|url=https://news.sina.com.cn/c/2019-10-04/doc-iicezuev0052697.shtml|date=2019-10-04|title=\u88ab\u8c03\u4f83\u5f00\u5f80\u5fb7\u56fd \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u67cf\u6797\u7ad9\u6ce8\u97f3\u6539\u4e3a\"bailin\"}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"|{{stl|WHM|Wuhan}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2013-12-28}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2019-9-25}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|49.693|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 37\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Elevated & underground\n|- \n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|6}}\" | '''[[Line 6 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 6</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Jinyinhu Park Station|lt=Jinyinhu Park|zh|\u91d1\u94f6\u6e56\u516c\u56ed\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Dongfeng Motor Corporation Station|lt=Dongfeng Motor Corporation|zh|\u4e1c\u98ce\u516c\u53f8\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2016-12-28}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|35.512|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 27\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|- \n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|7}}\" | '''[[Line 7 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 7</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Garden Expo North Station|lt=Garden Expo North|zh|\u56ed\u535a\u56ed\u5317\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"|{{ill|Qinglongshan Ditiexiaozhen Station|lt=Qinglongshan Ditiexiaozhen|zh|\u9752\u9f99\u5c71\u5730\u94c1\u5c0f\u9547\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2018-10-1}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2018-12-28}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|46.963|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 26\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|8}}\" | '''[[Line 8 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 8 Phase \u2160</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Jintan Road Station|lt=Jintan Road|zh|\u91d1\u6f6d\u8def\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Liyuan Station|lt=Liyuan|zh|\u68a8\u56ed\u7ad9 (\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2017-12-26}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|16.204|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|8}}\" | '''[[Line 8 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 8 Phase \u2162</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Yezhihu Station|lt=Yezhihu|zh|\u91ce\u82b7\u6e56\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Military Athletes' Village Station|lt=Military Athletes' Village|zh|\u519b\u8fd0\u6751\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2019-11-6}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|4.832|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|- \n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|11}}\" | '''[[Line 11 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 11</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Optics Valley Railway Station|lt=Optics Valley Railway Station|zh|\u5149\u8c37\u706b\u8f66\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Zuoling Station|lt=Zuoling|zh|\u5de6\u5cad\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2018-10-1}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|18.744|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|21}}\" | '''[[Yangluo line|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Yangluo Line</span>]]'''{{NoteTag|Yangluo Line is also known as Line 21.}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{stl|WHM|Houhu Boulevard}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Jintai Station|lt=Jintai|zh|\u91d1\u53f0\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2017-12-26}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|34.575|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Elevated & underground\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"5\"|'''Total'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''{{convert|339|km|mi||abbr=on}}''' \n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''228{{NoteTag|Transfer stations are counted repeatedly.}}'''\n|\n|}\n\n{{NoteFoot}}\n[[File:Train of Wuhan Metro Line 1 leaving Xunlimen station for Dazhi Road station.jpg|thumb|220px|Line 1 is fully elevated.]]\n===Line 1===\n{{main|Line 1 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 1 is a {{convert|37.788|km|abbr=on}} elevated urban rail line entirely located in the borough of [[Hankou]]. It runs a northwest\u2013southeast route that approximately parallels with [[Jiefang Avenue]] for its entire length. There are 27 planned stations, among which 25 are operational. Line 1 operates 33 four-car train sets, 12 of which are manufactured by [[Changchun Railway Vehicles]], and 21 by [[Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive Co., Ltd.]]\n\nOn July 28, 2004, the first phase of Line 1 began service from [[Huangpu Road]] to [[Zongguan]]. On July 28, 2010, Line 1 extended from both ends after the completion of phase 2.<ref>{{cite news | work = China Daily  | title = Wuhan light rail starts test run|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/hubei/2010-07/29/content_11068675.htm | author =  | date =  | accessdate =2010-07-31 }}</ref> The phase 3 expansion, which extends the northeast terminus to Hankou North Station, entered revenue service on May 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c11\u53f7\u7ebf\u6c49\u53e3\u5317\u5ef6\u957f\u7ebf\u660e\u65e5\u5f00\u901a  |url=http://news.ycwb.com/2014-05/27/content_6835502.htm |language=Chinese}}</ref> The phase 4 expansion, which extends to Jinghe Station from Dongwu Boulevard. The phase 4 opened on Dec 26th, 2017. Line 1's color is <span style=\"color:#0067a4;\">'''blue'''</span>.\n\n===Line 2===\n{{main|Line 2 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 2 is a {{convert|27.895|km|abbr=on}} underground subway connecting the boroughs of [[Hankou]] and [[Wuchang District|Wuchang]]. Upon completion, Line 2 was the first subway in [[People's Republic of China|China]] to cross the mighty [[Yangtze River]].<ref name=\"Subway to cross under Yangtze\" /> It runs in a northwest\u2013southeast route and crosses the Yangtze River near [[Jianghan Road]], and Jiyuqiao in Wuchang. Tunnel drilling concluded on February 26, 2012.<ref name=\"Subway to cross under Yangtze\">{{cite web | url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90882/7740600.html | title=Subway to cross under Yangtze | accessdate=March 5, 2012}}</ref> Revenue service of Line 2 began on December 28, 2012.<ref name=\"\u4eca\u65e510\u65f6\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c12\u53f7\u7ebf\u5f00\u901a \u6b66\u6c49\u8fc8\u5165\u5730\u94c1\u65f6\u4ee3(\u56fe)\">{{cite web | url=http://news.cnhubei.com/xw/zt/whdt/201212/t2392893.shtml |script-title=zh:\u4eca\u65e510\u65f6\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c12\u53f7\u7ebf\u5f00\u901a \u6b66\u6c49\u8fc8\u5165\u5730\u94c1\u65f6\u4ee3(\u56fe) | language=Chinese | accessdate=December 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://english.wh.gov.cn/publish/english/2012-11/28/1201211280900060014.html | title=Subway ticket price hearing held | accessdate=October 29, 2012}}</ref> Line 2 operates 41 six-car train sets, all of which were manufactured by [[Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive Co., Ltd.]]\n\nLine 2 is set to be extended towards both directions. The southern extension will bring the southeast terminus from [[Optics Valley Square]] to [[6th Gaoxin Road]], and the northwest extension plan will bring the northwest terminus from [[Jinyintan station|Jinyintan]] to [[Wuhan Tianhe International Airport]], providing convenient access for airport and residential areas en route. Early on, construction work on both extensions was expected to commence in 2013, and the tentative completion dates was set at 2015. In May 2014, it was reported that the construction work on the southern extension would start within 2014, with was the completion by February 19, 2019. Line 2's color is <span style=\"color:#e99bc1;\">'''pink'''</span>.<ref>\n\nNowadays, Line 2 only have 6 cars, but in the future, it is possible to add 2 cars to carry more people when the population of passengers are growing up, and 6 cars are not enough.\n\n[http://news.wuhan.fang.com/2014-05-28/12889126.htm \u5e74\u5185\u5f00\u5de52019\u5e74\u901a\u8f66 \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c12\u53f7\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u7ebf\u516c\u5e03\u5341\u7ad9\u70b9] (Work starting within this year; service opening in 2019. Ten stations announced for the Southern Extension of Line 2 of Wuhan Metro), 2014-05-28</ref>\n\n===Line 3===\n{{main|Line 3 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nOverall construction of Line 3 was approved by [[National Development and Reform Commission]] on Feb 23, 2012,<ref name=\"\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c13\u53f7\u7ebf\u83b7\u56fd\u5bb6\u53d1\u6539\u59d4\u6279\u590d \u4e00\u671f\u4e0b\u6708\u5168\u9762\u5f00\u5de5\">{{cite web | url=http://news.cnhubei.com/xwhbyw/xwwc/201202/t1981498.shtml |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c13\u53f7\u7ebf\u83b7\u56fd\u5bb6\u53d1\u6539\u59d4\u6279\u590d \u4e00\u671f\u4e0b\u6708\u5168\u9762\u5f00\u5de5 | accessdate=February 23, 2012}}</ref> and officially started on Mar 31, 2012.<ref name=\"\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c13\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u5929\u6b63\u5f0f\u52a8\u5efa \u9996\u7a7f\u6c49\u6c5f\u6c5f\u5e95\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cnhan.com/content/2012-03/31/content_1394194.htm |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c13\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u5929\u6b63\u5f0f\u52a8\u5efa \u9996\u7a7f\u6c49\u6c5f\u6c5f\u5e95 | accessdate=March 30, 2012}}</ref> Line 3 went into operation on December 28, 2015. Line 3's color is <span style=\"color:#dab866;\">'''dark yellow'''</span>.<ref name=\"Line 3\" /> Line 3 cars are Type B and manufactured by CRRC Changchun Railway Vehicles.\n\n===Line 4===\n{{main|Line 4 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 4 is mostly underground. It will run in an east\u2013west route serving the [[Hanyang District|Hanyang]] and [[Wuchang, Hubei|Wuchang]] distincts. The first phase linking [[Wuchang railway station|Wuchang]] and [[Wuhan railway station]]s opened on December 28, 2013; since that day,  all three main railway stations of Wuhan are connected by the Metro. The second phase of Line 4 will crossing the [[Yangtze River]] to Hanyang opened in 2014. Line 4's color is <span style=\"color:#b8d200;\">'''light green'''</span>.<ref name=\"\u4e8c\u671f\u958b\u901a\">{{cite web | publisher = \u834a\u695a\u7db2 |url=http://news.cnhubei.com/xw/wuhan/201411/t3108485.shtml | script-title=zh:\u5730\u94354\u865f\u7dab\u4e8c\u671f12\u670828\u65e5\u8a66\u904b\u71df \u7d50\u675f\u6f22\u967d\u7121\u5730\u9435\u6b77\u53f2 | accessdate=2014-12-11 | language =zh }}</ref> Line 4 cars are Type B and manufactured by CRRC Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive.\n\n===Line 6===\n{{main|Line 6 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 6 opened in 2016.<ref name=\"\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u673a\u573a\u7ebf\u53ca6\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a \u6e56\u5317\u79fb\u52a8\u5168\u9762\u5e03\u5c40\u7f51\u7edc\u8986\u76d6\"/>\nAnd it is the first line of Wuhan Metro to use high capacity A size trains with overhead lines. Line 6's color is <span style=\"color:#007733;\">'''green'''</span>. Line 6 uses Type A cars manufactured by CRRC Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive.\n\n===Line 7===\n{{main|Line 7 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 7 is a rapid transit line in Wuhan. The line runs from Garden Expo North in [[Dongxihu District]] to Qinglongshan Ditiexiaozhen in [[Jiangxia District]]. It serves residential & business areas such as Nanhu, Wuhan CBD and Wuhan Financial street. Line 7 reserves Wuhan Metro's highest capacity rolling stock to date featuring 8 Type-A car train sets accommodating 2480 people, compared to the standard 6 cars found on other lines. It is also the fastest urban line in the system, with trains capable of reaching the speed of 100 km/h (62 mph) compared to 80 km/h (50 mph) on other lines. <ref>http://en.hubei.gov.cn/news/newslist/201608/t20160812_881297.shtml</ref>\n\n===Line 8===\n{{main|Line 8 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nFull-scale construction was approved by [[National Development and Reform Commission]] on April 24, 2013. It was opened to the public on Dec 26, 2017. Line 8's color is <span style=\"color:#9aaead;\">'''grey'''</span>.<ref name=\"\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a8\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e00\u671f\u5de5\u7a0b\u5de5\u53ef\u83b7\u6279\">{{cite web | url=http://news.cnhubei.com/xw/wuhan/201304/t2553302.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5730\u94c18\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e00\u671f\u5de5\u7a0b\u83b7\u6279 \u8ba1\u5212\u4e8e2017\u5e74\u5efa\u6210\u901a\u8f66  | language=Chinese | accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref> Line 8 uses Type A cars manufactured by CRRC Changchun Railway Vehicles.\n\n===Line 11===\n{{main|Line 11 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 11 was opened on 1 October 2018 on National Day. Line 11 uses Type A cars manufactured by CRRC Changchun Railway Vehicles.\n\n===Yangluo Line===\n{{main|Yangluo line}}\nThe Yangluo Line is a rapid transit line that forms part of the Wuhan Metro system. Coloured <span style=\"color:#b60081;\">'''magenta'''</span> on the metro map, the line in its current form runs from Houhu Boulevard to Jintai, a total distance of {{convert|34.575|km|mi||abbr=on}}. The line connects the urban area of [[Hankou]] and [[Yangluo]], [[Xinzhou District]].\n\n==Services==\n===Opening hours===\nThe operating hours start at 6:00 on weekdays and 6:30 on weekends & holidays. The last trains of Yangluo Line depart from the terminis at 22:00 or 22:30, while other lines at 23:00. See the table below for more details. <ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.wuhanrt.com/public_forward.aspx??url=operation_public_list.aspx?tag=3&newtype=GetTime&dtag=menu_motion_1 |title =\u8fd0\u8425\u65f6\u523b\u8868}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!  colspan=\"2\"|Line\n! Weekdays \n! Weekends and holidays \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Yangluo Line \n|To Jintai\n|6:00 - 22:30\n|6:30 - 22:30\n|-\n|To Houhu Boulevard\n|6:00 - 22:00\n|6:30 - 22:00\n|-\n|  colspan=\"2\"|Other lines\n|6:00 - 23:00\n|6:30 - 23:00\n|}\n\n===Ticketing===\nFares vary based on the distance travelled. See the table below for more details.<ref name=\u7968\u52a1\u89c4\u5b9a></ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:90%; margin:0 auto;\"\n|{{Stacked bar|A1=4|T1=\u00a52<br>0 ~ 4 km|A2=4|T2=\u00a53<br>4 ~ 8 km|A3=4|T3=\u00a54<br>8 ~ 12 km|A4=6|T4=\u00a55<br>12 ~ 18 km|A5=6|T5=\u00a56<br>18 ~ 24 km|A6=8|T6=\u00a57<br>24 ~ 32 km|A7=8|T7=\u00a58<br>32 ~ 40 km|A8=10|T8=\u00a59<br>40 ~ 50 km|A9=20|T9=+ \u00a51<br>~ +20 km|Total=70}}\n|}\n\n====Discount====\nMost Passagers enter and exit the system using a [[proximity card]] called [[Wuhan Tong]], which is available at all metro stations. Passagers who pay for metro fare with a [[Wuhan Tong]] Card can receive a 10% discount.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hb.xinhuanet.com/2019-07/29/c_1124813193.htm|date=2019-07-29|title=\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u9664\u666e\u901a\u5361\u7968\u4ef79\u6298\u4f18\u60e0\u5916\u8fd8\u4e0a\u8c03\u5956\u52b1\u91d1\u989d}}</ref>Besides the metro, Passengers can also pay for tram, bus, and ferry fees by Wuhan Tong within Wuhan.\n\n====Multi-day pass====\nThere are three kinds of multi-day pass cards valid for one, three, and seven days respectively. \n*One-day pass: \u00a518 each and valid for 1 day;\n*Three-day pass: \u00a545 each and valid for 3 days;\n*Seven-day pass: \u00a590 each and valid for 7 days.\nCardholders may enjoy one, three, or seven days of unlimited rides in the metro system. The multi-day pass cards are available at the Customer Service Centres in the metro stations. In addition, a RMB 20 deposit is charged for each multi-day pass card.\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|footer=\n|lines=2\n|width=160\n|height=120\n|align=center\n|FILE:Ticket of Wuhan Metro.jpg|Single journey ticket \n|FILE:Wuhan City Smart Card 1.jpg|Wuhan Tong Card\n|FILE:Optics Valley Square Station Ticket Machine.jpg|Ticket vending machines\n|FILE:Qushuilou Station (2).jpg|Faregates\n|FILE:\u7434\u53f0\u7ad9\uff084\uff09.jpg|Customer service center\n|FILE:Zhiyin Station (4).jpg|Lift on the platform\n}}\n\n===Amenities===\n[[4G]] LTE services are provided in all stations and trains. As Line 1 was put into operation earlier, it lacks in some facilities. For more amenity information, plsease see the table below. It is worth mentioning that most of the restrooms are set outside the paid area.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Station\n! Restroom \n! Lift\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|Stations on Line 1\n|[[Youyi Road Station (Wuhan)|Youyi Road]], [[Liji North Road Station|Liji North Road]],<br> [[Chongren Road Station|Chongren Road]], [[Qiaokou Road Station|Qiaokou Road]], [[Taipingyang Station]] \n|unavailable\n|unequipped\n|-\n|{{STN|Huangpu Road}}, {{station|Sanyang Road}}, {{station|Dazhi Road}}, <br>{{station|Xunlimen}}, [[Zongguan Station]]<ref>The restroom is located in Station Hall of another line but shared by the two lines because it is an interchange station.\n</ref>\n|available\n|unequipped\n|-\n|The rest\n|available\n|equipped\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|Stations on other lines\n|available\n|equipped\n|}\n\n==Rolling stock==\n{{main|Wuhan Metro rolling stock}}\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|footer=\n|lines=2\n|width=190\n|height=140\n|align=center\n|File:Rolling stock NO. A62 of Wuhan Metro Line 1.jpg|Line 1\n|File:Rolling Stock of Wuhan Metro Line 2 2018-02-13 (2).jpg|Line 2\n|File:Rolling Stock of Wuhan Metro Line 3 2018-02-13.jpg|Line 3\n|File:NO. D51 train of Wuhan Metro Line 4.jpg|Line 4\n|file:Wuhan metro line 6 train.jpg|Line 6\n|File:NO.G03 Train of Wuhan Metro Line 7.jpg|Line 7\n|file:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c18\u53f7\u7ebf\u5217\u8f66(3).jpg|Line 8\n|File:Rolling Stock of Wuhan Metro Line 11 02APR2018 (05).jpg|Line 11\n|File:Rolling Stock of Wuhan Metro Yangluo Line (3).jpg|Yangluo Line \n|File:Train Interior of Wuhan Metro Line 7 (1).jpg|Train interior of Line 7 \n|File:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a11\u53f7\u7ebf\u8f66\u53a2\u5185\u90e8 (2).jpg|Train interior of Line 11\n|File:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c18\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e09\u91d1\u6f6d\u8f66\u8f86\u6bb5.jpg|Sanjintan Depot, Line 8\n}}\n\n==Signalling==\nWuhan Metro Line 1 is the first one equipped with [[moving block]] system in China.<ref>{{Cite web |url = http://m.gmw.cn/2019-07/17/content_1300520095.htm?p=1&s=gmwreco |title =15\u5e74\u4e86\uff0c\u6b66\u6c49\u4eba\u8d8a\u6765\u8d8a\u79bb\u4e0d\u5f00TA\uff01\u4f60\u8fd8\u8bb0\u5f97\u7b2c\u4e00\u6b21\u5417\uff1f|date = 2019-07-17|publisher = \u957f\u6c5f\u65e5\u62a5 |quote =1\u53f7\u7ebf\u662f\u56fd\u5185\u9996\u6761\u91c7\u7528\u79fb\u52a8\u95ed\u585e\u4fe1\u53f7\u7cfb\u7edf\u7ebf\u8def }}</ref> All the lines are equipped with [[Communications-based train control|CBTC]]. In the future, [[List of automated train systems|a fully automated, driverless train system (GoA4)]], provided by Traffic Control Technology Corporation Limited, will be applied to Line 5.<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/T7-TBzvcfQTJZanvzYoAQg|title = \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c15\u53f7\u7ebf\u6709\u671b\u53d6\u6d88\u9a7e\u9a76\u5ba4\uff0c\u5b9e\u73b0\u771f\u6b63\u65e0\u4eba\u9a7e\u9a76\uff01|author =|date = 2017-08-03|publisher =\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1}}</ref>\n\n==Ridership==\n{{ multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width = 220\n|image1=Wuhan Business District Station Rush Hour (1).jpg|caption1=\n|image2=Wuhan Business District Station Rush Hour (2).jpg|caption2=Passengers waiting in line for the train of Line 3 at rush hours.\n}}\nDue to new lines or sections coming into operation every year, the ridership of the whole network continues to grow. After Line 3 opened on {{date|2015-12-28}}, the transferring ridership started being included in the total ridership. \n{{Bar chart\n| title       = Average daily ridership\n| label_type  = Year\n| data_type   = Ridership (million)\n| bar_width   = 35\n| width_units = em\n| data_max    = 4\n| label1   = 2013<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=1050|title=2013\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2017-11-22|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data1    = 0.87\n| label2   = 2014<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=1049|title=2014\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2017-11-22|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data2    = 1.08\n| label3   = 2015<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=1048|title=2015\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2017-11-22|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data3    = 1.20\n| label4   = 2016<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=1047|title=2016\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2017-11-22|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data4   = 1.96\n| label5   = 2017<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=13532|title=2017\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2018-04-19|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data5    = 2.54\n| label6   = 2018<ref name=2018report>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=16219|title=2018\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2019-04-07|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data6    =3.07\n| label7   = 2019<ref>{{Cite web |url =https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/7aCHDocl1-JvLA9QEJPQsw|title=\u5168\u6765\u4e86\uff012019\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u8fd0\u91cf\u603b\u7ed3|date=2020-02-15|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data7    = 3.35\n}}\n\n==Future expansion==\n[[file:\u6b66\u6c49\u5e02\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u7b2c\u56db\u671f\u5efa\u8bbe\u89c4\u5212\uff082019-2024 \u5e74\uff09\u793a\u610f\u56fe.png|thumb|220px|Wuhan Metro Phase IV Construction Plan Diagram (2019-2024), in which the red and purple lines with a total length of 198.4km were newly approved on {{date|2018-12-25}}, and the other gray parts are under construction or in operation]]\nA number of lines are under construction. Line 12 will be a [[Circle route|loop line]]. Line 5 is proposed to use [[Automated metro|automated driverless trains]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hb.chinanews.com/news/2018/0516/303486.html |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u65b0\u7f51\u6e56\u5317 \u6e56\u5317\u65b0\u95fb\u7f51 \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u8fdb\u5165\u5168\u81ea\u52a8\u9a7e\u9a76\u65f6\u4ee3 5\u53f7\u7ebf\u6709\u671b\"\u5c1d\u9c9c\"|website=www.hb.chinanews.com|access-date=2018-05-21}}</ref> Line 9, 10, as well as Line 13, are being planned by the municipal authority.<ref name=\"\u56fe\u6587\uff1a\u5341\u4e8c\u4e94\u671f\u95f4,\u6b66\u6c49\u5c06\u6295\u8d44491\u4ebf\u65b0\u5efa\u8fdc\u57ce\u533a8\u6761\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\">{{cite web | url=http://news.cnhubei.com/ctjb/ctjbsgk/ctjb01/201203/t2008312.shtml | script-title=zh:\u5341\u4e8c\u4e94\u671f\u95f4,\u6b66\u6c49\u5c06\u6295\u8d44491\u4ebf\u65b0\u5efa\u8fdc\u57ce\u533a8\u6761\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a |language=Chinese |accessdate=2012-05-01}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"height:240pt;\"\n! style=\"width:150pt;\"| Lines and Liveries\n! style=\"width:200pt;\" colspan=\"2\"| Termini\n! Operational by\n! Total Length<br/>{{small|in [[Kilometre|km]]}}\n! Stations\n! Status\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center ; background:#{{WHM color|6}}\"| [[Line 6, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Phase 2 of Line 6</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zoumaling}}\n| {{WHM stations|Jinyinhu Park}}\n| 2020\n| 15.3\n| 9\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|8}}\" | [[Line 8, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Phase 2 of Line 8 </span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Liyuan}}\n| {{WHM stations|Yezhihu}}\n| 2020\n| 17.4\n| 11\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|11}}\" rowspan=\"3\" |  [[Line 11, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:black\">Phase 3 of Line 11</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zuoling}}\n| [[Gedian South railway station|Gedian South Railway Station]] (in [[Ezhou]] city)\n| 2020\n| 3.7\n| 1\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| {{WHM stations|Huangjinkou}}\n| {{WHM stations|Xinhanyang Railway Station}}\n| TBD\n| 2.2\n| 2\n| bgcolor=\"lightblue\"| Approved\n|-\n| {{WHM stations|Jiang'an Road}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuchang}}\n| TBD\n| 4\n| 2\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|5}}\" |[[Line 5, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 5 </span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|South Third Ring Road}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| 2021\n| 33.57\n| 25\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|11}}\" |  [[Line 11, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:black\">Phase 2 of Line 11</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Wuchang}}\n| [[Guanggu railway station|Optics Valley Railway Station]]\n| 2021\n| 12.41\n| 7\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|16}}\" |  [[Line 16, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 16</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|South International Expo Center}}\n| {{WHM stations|Zhoujiahe}}\n| 2021\n| 32.4\n| 12\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|12}}\" |  [[Line 12, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 12 </span>]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| ''loop line''\n| 2023\n| 60.4\n| 35\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|19}}\" | [[Line 19, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 19 </span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| {{WHM stations|Optics Valley Free Trade Zone}}\n| 2023\n| 24.45\n| 9\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|7}}\" | [[Line 7, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Northern extension of Line 7</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Machi}}\n| {{WHM stations|Huangpi Square}}\n| 2024\n| 36\n| 10\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|10}}\" |  [[Line 10, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Xingang Line</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| {{WHM stations|Shigang}}\n| 2025\n| 26.2\n| 10\n| bgcolor=\"lightblue\"| Approved\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|10}}\" |  [[Line 10, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 10</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Changfu}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| 2025\n| 61.4\n| 29\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|21}}\" |  [[Yangluo line|<span STYLE=\" color:white\"> Phase 2 of Yangluo Line</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zhongyi Road}}\n| {{WHM stations|Houhu Boulevard}}\n| TBD\n| 3.2\n| 2\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|13}}\" |  [[Line 13, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 13</span>]]\n| [[New Hanyang railway station|New Hanyang Railway Station]]\n| {{WHM stations|Future Tech-city}}\n| TBD\n| 40.4\n| 27\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|14}}\" |  [[Line 14, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 14</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zhuyehai}}\n| {{WHM stations|Dijiao}}\n| TBD\n| 27.2\n| 21\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|20}}\" |  [[Line 20, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 20</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Tianhe International Airport}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| TBD\n| 30.3\n| 6\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|}\n\n==Station==\nAlmost all stations, except the stations on Line 1, are equipped with [[platform screen door]]s. There is a plan that stations on Line 1 will be equipped with [[platform screen door]]s in the future.<ref>{{Cite web |url = http://news.cjn.cn/sywh/201505/t2642859.htm |title = \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c11\u53f7\u7ebf\u5c06\u5168\u7ebf\u5b89\u88c5\u7ad9\u53f0\u5b89\u5168\u95e8 \u4e0e\u5faa\u793c\u95e8\u7ad9\u4e00\u81f4 |author =\u9676\u5e38\u5b81\uff1b\u80e1\u7434|date = 2015-05-04 |publisher = \u6b66\u6c49\u6668\u62a5 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url =http://hb.sina.cn/news/2016-01-16/detail-ifxnqrkc6501288.d.html?from=wap#_cnbk_ |title = \u6b66\u6c49\u5973\u4e58\u5ba2\u610f\u5916\u8dcc\u4e0b1\u53f7\u7ebf\u7ad9\u53f0 \u8f7b\u8f68\u5b89\u5168\u95e8\u8fdf\u8fdf\u4e0d\u88c5 |author =\u5218\u5b5d\u658c\uff1b\u9ec4\u58eb\u5cf0 |date = 2016-01-06 |publisher=\u695a\u5929\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5}}</ref> The metro stations are equipped to be disabled and elderly friendly, with automatic fare collection system, announcement system, electronic display boards, escalators and lifts. The stations are equipped with non-slippery flooring with grip-rails, audio announcements and Braille facilities to help visually challenged passengers. \n\n===Gallery===\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|footer=\n|lines=2\n|width=200\n|height=150\n|