8}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|46.963|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 26\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|8}}\" | '''[[Line 8 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 8 Phase \u2160</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Jintan Road Station|lt=Jintan Road|zh|\u91d1\u6f6d\u8def\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Liyuan Station|lt=Liyuan|zh|\u68a8\u56ed\u7ad9 (\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1)}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2017-12-26}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|16.204|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|8}}\" | '''[[Line 8 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 8 Phase \u2162</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Yezhihu Station|lt=Yezhihu|zh|\u91ce\u82b7\u6e56\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Military Athletes' Village Station|lt=Military Athletes' Village|zh|\u519b\u8fd0\u6751\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2019-11-6}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|4.832|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|- \n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|11}}\" | '''[[Line 11 (Wuhan Metro)|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 11</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Optics Valley Railway Station|lt=Optics Valley Railway Station|zh|\u5149\u8c37\u706b\u8f66\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Zuoling Station|lt=Zuoling|zh|\u5de6\u5cad\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2018-10-1}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|18.744|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Underground\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|21}}\" | '''[[Yangluo line|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Yangluo Line</span>]]'''{{NoteTag|Yangluo Line is also known as Line 21.}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{stl|WHM|Houhu Boulevard}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{ill|Jintai Station|lt=Jintai|zh|\u91d1\u53f0\u7ad9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2017-12-26}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|34.575|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Elevated & underground\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"5\"|'''Total'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''{{convert|339|km|mi||abbr=on}}''' \n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''228{{NoteTag|Transfer stations are counted repeatedly.}}'''\n|\n|}\n\n{{NoteFoot}}\n[[File:Train of Wuhan Metro Line 1 leaving Xunlimen station for Dazhi Road station.jpg|thumb|220px|Line 1 is fully elevated.]]\n===Line 1===\n{{main|Line 1 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 1 is a {{convert|37.788|km|abbr=on}} elevated urban rail line entirely located in the borough of [[Hankou]]. It runs a northwest\u2013southeast route that approximately parallels with [[Jiefang Avenue]] for its entire length. There are 27 planned stations, among which 25 are operational. Line 1 operates 33 four-car train sets, 12 of which are manufactured by [[Changchun Railway Vehicles]], and 21 by [[Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive Co., Ltd.]]\n\nOn July 28, 2004, the first phase of Line 1 began service from [[Huangpu Road]] to [[Zongguan]]. On July 28, 2010, Line 1 extended from both ends after the completion of phase 2.<ref>{{cite news | work = China Daily  | title = Wuhan light rail starts test run|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/hubei/2010-07/29/content_11068675.htm | author =  | date =  | accessdate =2010-07-31 }}</ref> The phase 3 expansion, which extends the northeast terminus to Hankou North Station, entered revenue service on May 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c11\u53f7\u7ebf\u6c49\u53e3\u5317\u5ef6\u957f\u7ebf\u660e\u65e5\u5f00\u901a  |url=http://news.ycwb.com/2014-05/27/content_6835502.htm |language=Chinese}}</ref> The phase 4 expansion, which extends to Jinghe Station from Dongwu Boulevard. The phase 4 opened on Dec 26th, 2017. Line 1's color is <span style=\"color:#0067a4;\">'''blue'''</span>.\n\n===Line 2===\n{{main|Line 2 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 2 is a {{convert|27.895|km|abbr=on}} underground subway connecting the boroughs of [[Hankou]] and [[Wuchang District|Wuchang]]. Upon completion, Line 2 was the first subway in [[People's Republic of China|China]] to cross the mighty [[Yangtze River]].<ref name=\"Subway to cross under Yangtze\" /> It runs in a northwest\u2013southeast route and crosses the Yangtze River near [[Jianghan Road]], and Jiyuqiao in Wuchang. Tunnel drilling concluded on February 26, 2012.<ref name=\"Subway to cross under Yangtze\">{{cite web | url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90882/7740600.html | title=Subway to cross under Yangtze | accessdate=March 5, 2012}}</ref> Revenue service of Line 2 began on December 28, 2012.<ref name=\"\u4eca\u65e510\u65f6\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c12\u53f7\u7ebf\u5f00\u901a \u6b66\u6c49\u8fc8\u5165\u5730\u94c1\u65f6\u4ee3(\u56fe)\">{{cite web | url=http://news.cnhubei.com/xw/zt/whdt/201212/t2392893.shtml |script-title=zh:\u4eca\u65e510\u65f6\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c12\u53f7\u7ebf\u5f00\u901a \u6b66\u6c49\u8fc8\u5165\u5730\u94c1\u65f6\u4ee3(\u56fe) | language=Chinese | accessdate=December 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://english.wh.gov.cn/publish/english/2012-11/28/1201211280900060014.html | title=Subway ticket price hearing held | accessdate=October 29, 2012}}</ref> Line 2 operates 41 six-car train sets, all of which were manufactured by [[Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive Co., Ltd.]]\n\nLine 2 is set to be extended towards both directions. The southern extension will bring the southeast terminus from [[Optics Valley Square]] to [[6th Gaoxin Road]], and the northwest extension plan will bring the northwest terminus from [[Jinyintan station|Jinyintan]] to [[Wuhan Tianhe International Airport]], providing convenient access for airport and residential areas en route. Early on, construction work on both extensions was expected to commence in 2013, and the tentative completion dates was set at 2015. In May 2014, it was reported that the construction work on the southern extension would start within 2014, with was the completion by February 19, 2019. Line 2's color is <span style=\"color:#e99bc1;\">'''pink'''</span>.<ref>\n\nNowadays, Line 2 only have 6 cars, but in the future, it is possible to add 2 cars to carry more people when the population of passengers are growing up, and 6 cars are not enough.\n\n[http://news.wuhan.fang.com/2014-05-28/12889126.htm \u5e74\u5185\u5f00\u5de52019\u5e74\u901a\u8f66 \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c12\u53f7\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u7ebf\u516c\u5e03\u5341\u7ad9\u70b9] (Work starting within this year; service opening in 2019. Ten stations announced for the Southern Extension of Line 2 of Wuhan Metro), 2014-05-28</ref>\n\n===Line 3===\n{{main|Line 3 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nOverall construction of Line 3 was approved by [[National Development and Reform Commission]] on Feb 23, 2012,<ref name=\"\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c13\u53f7\u7ebf\u83b7\u56fd\u5bb6\u53d1\u6539\u59d4\u6279\u590d \u4e00\u671f\u4e0b\u6708\u5168\u9762\u5f00\u5de5\">{{cite web | url=http://news.cnhubei.com/xwhbyw/xwwc/201202/t1981498.shtml |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c13\u53f7\u7ebf\u83b7\u56fd\u5bb6\u53d1\u6539\u59d4\u6279\u590d \u4e00\u671f\u4e0b\u6708\u5168\u9762\u5f00\u5de5 | accessdate=February 23, 2012}}</ref> and officially started on Mar 31, 2012.<ref name=\"\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c13\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u5929\u6b63\u5f0f\u52a8\u5efa \u9996\u7a7f\u6c49\u6c5f\u6c5f\u5e95\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cnhan.com/content/2012-03/31/content_1394194.htm |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c13\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u5929\u6b63\u5f0f\u52a8\u5efa \u9996\u7a7f\u6c49\u6c5f\u6c5f\u5e95 | accessdate=March 30, 2012}}</ref> Line 3 went into operation on December 28, 2015. Line 3's color is <span style=\"color:#dab866;\">'''dark yellow'''</span>.<ref name=\"Line 3\" /> Line 3 cars are Type B and manufactured by CRRC Changchun Railway Vehicles.\n\n===Line 4===\n{{main|Line 4 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 4 is mostly underground. It will run in an east\u2013west route serving the [[Hanyang District|Hanyang]] and [[Wuchang, Hubei|Wuchang]] distincts. The first phase linking [[Wuchang railway station|Wuchang]] and [[Wuhan railway station]]s opened on December 28, 2013; since that day,  all three main railway stations of Wuhan are connected by the Metro. The second phase of Line 4 will crossing the [[Yangtze River]] to Hanyang opened in 2014. Line 4's color is <span style=\"color:#b8d200;\">'''light green'''</span>.<ref name=\"\u4e8c\u671f\u958b\u901a\">{{cite web | publisher = \u834a\u695a\u7db2 |url=http://news.cnhubei.com/xw/wuhan/201411/t3108485.shtml | script-title=zh:\u5730\u94354\u865f\u7dab\u4e8c\u671f12\u670828\u65e5\u8a66\u904b\u71df \u7d50\u675f\u6f22\u967d\u7121\u5730\u9435\u6b77\u53f2 | accessdate=2014-12-11 | language =zh }}</ref> Line 4 cars are Type B and manufactured by CRRC Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive.\n\n===Line 6===\n{{main|Line 6 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 6 opened in 2016.<ref name=\"\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u673a\u573a\u7ebf\u53ca6\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a \u6e56\u5317\u79fb\u52a8\u5168\u9762\u5e03\u5c40\u7f51\u7edc\u8986\u76d6\"/>\nAnd it is the first line of Wuhan Metro to use high capacity A size trains with overhead lines. Line 6's color is <span style=\"color:#007733;\">'''green'''</span>. Line 6 uses Type A cars manufactured by CRRC Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive.\n\n===Line 7===\n{{main|Line 7 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 7 is a rapid transit line in Wuhan. The line runs from Garden Expo North in [[Dongxihu District]] to Qinglongshan Ditiexiaozhen in [[Jiangxia District]]. It serves residential & business areas such as Nanhu, Wuhan CBD and Wuhan Financial street. Line 7 reserves Wuhan Metro's highest capacity rolling stock to date featuring 8 Type-A car train sets accommodating 2480 people, compared to the standard 6 cars found on other lines. It is also the fastest urban line in the system, with trains capable of reaching the speed of 100 km/h (62 mph) compared to 80 km/h (50 mph) on other lines. <ref>http://en.hubei.gov.cn/news/newslist/201608/t20160812_881297.shtml</ref>\n\n===Line 8===\n{{main|Line 8 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nFull-scale construction was approved by [[National Development and Reform Commission]] on April 24, 2013. It was opened to the public on Dec 26, 2017. Line 8's color is <span style=\"color:#9aaead;\">'''grey'''</span>.<ref name=\"\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a8\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e00\u671f\u5de5\u7a0b\u5de5\u53ef\u83b7\u6279\">{{cite web | url=http://news.cnhubei.com/xw/wuhan/201304/t2553302.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5730\u94c18\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e00\u671f\u5de5\u7a0b\u83b7\u6279 \u8ba1\u5212\u4e8e2017\u5e74\u5efa\u6210\u901a\u8f66  | language=Chinese | accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref> Line 8 uses Type A cars manufactured by CRRC Changchun Railway Vehicles.\n\n===Line 11===\n{{main|Line 11 (Wuhan Metro)}}\nLine 11 was opened on 1 October 2018 on National Day. Line 11 uses Type A cars manufactured by CRRC Changchun Railway Vehicles.\n\n===Yangluo Line===\n{{main|Yangluo line}}\nThe Yangluo Line is a rapid transit line that forms part of the Wuhan Metro system. Coloured <span style=\"color:#b60081;\">'''magenta'''</span> on the metro map, the line in its current form runs from Houhu Boulevard to Jintai, a total distance of {{convert|34.575|km|mi||abbr=on}}. The line connects the urban area of [[Hankou]] and [[Yangluo]], [[Xinzhou District]].\n\n==Services==\n===Opening hours===\nThe operating hours start at 6:00 on weekdays and 6:30 on weekends & holidays. The last trains of Yangluo Line depart from the terminis at 22:00 or 22:30, while other lines at 23:00. See the table below for more details. <ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.wuhanrt.com/public_forward.aspx??url=operation_public_list.aspx?tag=3&newtype=GetTime&dtag=menu_motion_1 |title =\u8fd0\u8425\u65f6\u523b\u8868}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!  colspan=\"2\"|Line\n! Weekdays \n! Weekends and holidays \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Yangluo Line \n|To Jintai\n|6:00 - 22:30\n|6:30 - 22:30\n|-\n|To Houhu Boulevard\n|6:00 - 22:00\n|6:30 - 22:00\n|-\n|  colspan=\"2\"|Other lines\n|6:00 - 23:00\n|6:30 - 23:00\n|}\n\n===Ticketing===\nFares vary based on the distance travelled. See the table below for more details.<ref name=\u7968\u52a1\u89c4\u5b9a></ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:90%; margin:0 auto;\"\n|{{Stacked bar|A1=4|T1=\u00a52<br>0 ~ 4 km|A2=4|T2=\u00a53<br>4 ~ 8 km|A3=4|T3=\u00a54<br>8 ~ 12 km|A4=6|T4=\u00a55<br>12 ~ 18 km|A5=6|T5=\u00a56<br>18 ~ 24 km|A6=8|T6=\u00a57<br>24 ~ 32 km|A7=8|T7=\u00a58<br>32 ~ 40 km|A8=10|T8=\u00a59<br>40 ~ 50 km|A9=20|T9=+ \u00a51<br>~ +20 km|Total=70}}\n|}\n\n====Discount====\nMost Passagers enter and exit the system using a [[proximity card]] called [[Wuhan Tong]], which is available at all metro stations. Passagers who pay for metro fare with a [[Wuhan Tong]] Card can receive a 10% discount.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hb.xinhuanet.com/2019-07/29/c_1124813193.htm|date=2019-07-29|title=\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u9664\u666e\u901a\u5361\u7968\u4ef79\u6298\u4f18\u60e0\u5916\u8fd8\u4e0a\u8c03\u5956\u52b1\u91d1\u989d}}</ref>Besides the metro, Passengers can also pay for tram, bus, and ferry fees by Wuhan Tong within Wuhan.\n\n====Multi-day pass====\nThere are three kinds of multi-day pass cards valid for one, three, and seven days respectively. \n*One-day pass: \u00a518 each and valid for 1 day;\n*Three-day pass: \u00a545 each and valid for 3 days;\n*Seven-day pass: \u00a590 each and valid for 7 days.\nCardholders may enjoy one, three, or seven days of unlimited rides in the metro system. The multi-day pass cards are available at the Customer Service Centres in the metro stations. In addition, a RMB 20 deposit is charged for each multi-day pass card.\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|footer=\n|lines=2\n|width=160\n|height=120\n|align=center\n|FILE:Ticket of Wuhan Metro.jpg|Single journey ticket \n|FILE:Wuhan City Smart Card 1.jpg|Wuhan Tong Card\n|FILE:Optics Valley Square Station Ticket Machine.jpg|Ticket vending machines\n|FILE:Qushuilou Station (2).jpg|Faregates\n|FILE:\u7434\u53f0\u7ad9\uff084\uff09.jpg|Customer service center\n|FILE:Zhiyin Station (4).jpg|Lift on the platform\n}}\n\n===Amenities===\n[[4G]] LTE services are provided in all stations and trains. As Line 1 was put into operation earlier, it lacks in some facilities. For more amenity information, plsease see the table below. It is worth mentioning that most of the restrooms are set outside the paid area.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Station\n! Restroom \n! Lift\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|Stations on Line 1\n|[[Youyi Road Station (Wuhan)|Youyi Road]], [[Liji North Road Station|Liji North Road]],<br> [[Chongren Road Station|Chongren Road]], [[Qiaokou Road Station|Qiaokou Road]], [[Taipingyang Station]] \n|unavailable\n|unequipped\n|-\n|{{STN|Huangpu Road}}, {{station|Sanyang Road}}, {{station|Dazhi Road}}, <br>{{station|Xunlimen}}, [[Zongguan Station]]<ref>The restroom is located in Station Hall of another line but shared by the two lines because it is an interchange station.\n</ref>\n|available\n|unequipped\n|-\n|The rest\n|available\n|equipped\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|Stations on other lines\n|available\n|equipped\n|}\n\n==Rolling stock==\n{{main|Wuhan Metro rolling stock}}\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|footer=\n|lines=2\n|width=190\n|height=140\n|align=center\n|File:Rolling stock NO. A62 of Wuhan Metro Line 1.jpg|Line 1\n|File:Rolling Stock of Wuhan Metro Line 2 2018-02-13 (2).jpg|Line 2\n|File:Rolling Stock of Wuhan Metro Line 3 2018-02-13.jpg|Line 3\n|File:NO. D51 train of Wuhan Metro Line 4.jpg|Line 4\n|file:Wuhan metro line 6 train.jpg|Line 6\n|File:NO.G03 Train of Wuhan Metro Line 7.jpg|Line 7\n|file:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c18\u53f7\u7ebf\u5217\u8f66(3).jpg|Line 8\n|File:Rolling Stock of Wuhan Metro Line 11 02APR2018 (05).jpg|Line 11\n|File:Rolling Stock of Wuhan Metro Yangluo Line (3).jpg|Yangluo Line \n|File:Train Interior of Wuhan Metro Line 7 (1).jpg|Train interior of Line 7 \n|File:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a11\u53f7\u7ebf\u8f66\u53a2\u5185\u90e8 (2).jpg|Train interior of Line 11\n|File:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c18\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e09\u91d1\u6f6d\u8f66\u8f86\u6bb5.jpg|Sanjintan Depot, Line 8\n}}\n\n==Signalling==\nWuhan Metro Line 1 is the first one equipped with [[moving block]] system in China.<ref>{{Cite web |url = http://m.gmw.cn/2019-07/17/content_1300520095.htm?p=1&s=gmwreco |title =15\u5e74\u4e86\uff0c\u6b66\u6c49\u4eba\u8d8a\u6765\u8d8a\u79bb\u4e0d\u5f00TA\uff01\u4f60\u8fd8\u8bb0\u5f97\u7b2c\u4e00\u6b21\u5417\uff1f|date = 2019-07-17|publisher = \u957f\u6c5f\u65e5\u62a5 |quote =1\u53f7\u7ebf\u662f\u56fd\u5185\u9996\u6761\u91c7\u7528\u79fb\u52a8\u95ed\u585e\u4fe1\u53f7\u7cfb\u7edf\u7ebf\u8def }}</ref> All the lines are equipped with [[Communications-based train control|CBTC]]. In the future, [[List of automated train systems|a fully automated, driverless train system (GoA4)]], provided by Traffic Control Technology Corporation Limited, will be applied to Line 5.<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/T7-TBzvcfQTJZanvzYoAQg|title = \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c15\u53f7\u7ebf\u6709\u671b\u53d6\u6d88\u9a7e\u9a76\u5ba4\uff0c\u5b9e\u73b0\u771f\u6b63\u65e0\u4eba\u9a7e\u9a76\uff01|author =|date = 2017-08-03|publisher =\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1}}</ref>\n\n==Ridership==\n{{ multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width = 220\n|image1=Wuhan Business District Station Rush Hour (1).jpg|caption1=\n|image2=Wuhan Business District Station Rush Hour (2).jpg|caption2=Passengers waiting in line for the train of Line 3 at rush hours.\n}}\nDue to new lines or sections coming into operation every year, the ridership of the whole network continues to grow. After Line 3 opened on {{date|2015-12-28}}, the transferring ridership started being included in the total ridership. \n{{Bar chart\n| title       = Average daily ridership\n| label_type  = Year\n| data_type   = Ridership (million)\n| bar_width   = 35\n| width_units = em\n| data_max    = 4\n| label1   = 2013<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=1050|title=2013\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2017-11-22|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data1    = 0.87\n| label2   = 2014<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=1049|title=2014\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2017-11-22|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data2    = 1.08\n| label3   = 2015<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=1048|title=2015\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2017-11-22|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data3    = 1.20\n| label4   = 2016<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=1047|title=2016\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2017-11-22|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data4   = 1.96\n| label5   = 2017<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=13532|title=2017\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2018-04-19|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data5    = 2.54\n| label6   = 2018<ref name=2018report>{{Cite web |url =http://www.camet.org.cn/index.php?m=content&c=index&a=show&catid=18&id=16219|title=2018\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u62a5\u544a|date=2019-04-07|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data6    =3.07\n| label7   = 2019<ref>{{Cite web |url =https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/7aCHDocl1-JvLA9QEJPQsw|title=\u5168\u6765\u4e86\uff012019\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u8fd0\u91cf\u603b\u7ed3|date=2020-02-15|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a}}</ref>\n| data7    = 3.35\n}}\n\n==Future expansion==\n[[file:\u6b66\u6c49\u5e02\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u7b2c\u56db\u671f\u5efa\u8bbe\u89c4\u5212\uff082019-2024 \u5e74\uff09\u793a\u610f\u56fe.png|thumb|220px|Wuhan Metro Phase IV Construction Plan Diagram (2019-2024), in which the red and purple lines with a total length of 198.4km were newly approved on {{date|2018-12-25}}, and the other gray parts are under construction or in operation]]\nA number of lines are under construction. Line 12 will be a [[Circle route|loop line]]. Line 5 is proposed to use [[Automated metro|automated driverless trains]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hb.chinanews.com/news/2018/0516/303486.html |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u65b0\u7f51\u6e56\u5317 \u6e56\u5317\u65b0\u95fb\u7f51 \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u8fdb\u5165\u5168\u81ea\u52a8\u9a7e\u9a76\u65f6\u4ee3 5\u53f7\u7ebf\u6709\u671b\"\u5c1d\u9c9c\"|website=www.hb.chinanews.com|access-date=2018-05-21}}</ref> Line 9, 10, as well as Line 13, are being planned by the municipal authority.<ref name=\"\u56fe\u6587\uff1a\u5341\u4e8c\u4e94\u671f\u95f4,\u6b66\u6c49\u5c06\u6295\u8d44491\u4ebf\u65b0\u5efa\u8fdc\u57ce\u533a8\u6761\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\">{{cite web | url=http://news.cnhubei.com/ctjb/ctjbsgk/ctjb01/201203/t2008312.shtml | script-title=zh:\u5341\u4e8c\u4e94\u671f\u95f4,\u6b66\u6c49\u5c06\u6295\u8d44491\u4ebf\u65b0\u5efa\u8fdc\u57ce\u533a8\u6761\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a |language=Chinese |accessdate=2012-05-01}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"height:240pt;\"\n! style=\"width:150pt;\"| Lines and Liveries\n! style=\"width:200pt;\" colspan=\"2\"| Termini\n! Operational by\n! Total Length<br/>{{small|in [[Kilometre|km]]}}\n! Stations\n! Status\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center ; background:#{{WHM color|6}}\"| [[Line 6, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Phase 2 of Line 6</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zoumaling}}\n| {{WHM stations|Jinyinhu Park}}\n| 2020\n| 15.3\n| 9\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|8}}\" | [[Line 8, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Phase 2 of Line 8 </span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Liyuan}}\n| {{WHM stations|Yezhihu}}\n| 2020\n| 17.4\n| 11\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|11}}\" rowspan=\"3\" |  [[Line 11, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:black\">Phase 3 of Line 11</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zuoling}}\n| [[Gedian South railway station|Gedian South Railway Station]] (in [[Ezhou]] city)\n| 2020\n| 3.7\n| 1\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| {{WHM stations|Huangjinkou}}\n| {{WHM stations|Xinhanyang Railway Station}}\n| TBD\n| 2.2\n| 2\n| bgcolor=\"lightblue\"| Approved\n|-\n| {{WHM stations|Jiang'an Road}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuchang}}\n| TBD\n| 4\n| 2\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|5}}\" |[[Line 5, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 5 </span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|South Third Ring Road}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| 2021\n| 33.57\n| 25\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|11}}\" |  [[Line 11, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:black\">Phase 2 of Line 11</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Wuchang}}\n| [[Guanggu railway station|Optics Valley Railway Station]]\n| 2021\n| 12.41\n| 7\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|16}}\" |  [[Line 16, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 16</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|South International Expo Center}}\n| {{WHM stations|Zhoujiahe}}\n| 2021\n| 32.4\n| 12\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|12}}\" |  [[Line 12, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 12 </span>]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| ''loop line''\n| 2023\n| 60.4\n| 35\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|19}}\" | [[Line 19, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 19 </span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| {{WHM stations|Optics Valley Free Trade Zone}}\n| 2023\n| 24.45\n| 9\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|7}}\" | [[Line 7, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Northern extension of Line 7</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Machi}}\n| {{WHM stations|Huangpi Square}}\n| 2024\n| 36\n| 10\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|10}}\" |  [[Line 10, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Xingang Line</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| {{WHM stations|Shigang}}\n| 2025\n| 26.2\n| 10\n| bgcolor=\"lightblue\"| Approved\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|10}}\" |  [[Line 10, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 10</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Changfu}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| 2025\n| 61.4\n| 29\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|21}}\" |  [[Yangluo line|<span STYLE=\" color:white\"> Phase 2 of Yangluo Line</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zhongyi Road}}\n| {{WHM stations|Houhu Boulevard}}\n| TBD\n| 3.2\n| 2\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|13}}\" |  [[Line 13, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 13</span>]]\n| [[New Hanyang railway station|New Hanyang Railway Station]]\n| {{WHM stations|Future Tech-city}}\n| TBD\n| 40.4\n| 27\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|14}}\" |  [[Line 14, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 14</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zhuyehai}}\n| {{WHM stations|Dijiao}}\n| TBD\n| 27.2\n| 21\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|20}}\" |  [[Line 20, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 20</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Tianhe International Airport}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| TBD\n| 30.3\n| 6\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|}\n\n==Station==\nAlmost all stations, except the stations on Line 1, are equipped with [[platform screen door]]s. There is a plan that stations on Line 1 will be equipped with [[platform screen door]]s in the future.<ref>{{Cite web |url = http://news.cjn.cn/sywh/201505/t2642859.htm |title = \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c11\u53f7\u7ebf\u5c06\u5168\u7ebf\u5b89\u88c5\u7ad9\u53f0\u5b89\u5168\u95e8 \u4e0e\u5faa\u793c\u95e8\u7ad9\u4e00\u81f4 |author =\u9676\u5e38\u5b81\uff1b\u80e1\u7434|date = 2015-05-04 |publisher = \u6b66\u6c49\u6668\u62a5 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url =http://hb.sina.cn/news/2016-01-16/detail-ifxnqrkc6501288.d.html?from=wap#_cnbk_ |title = \u6b66\u6c49\u5973\u4e58\u5ba2\u610f\u5916\u8dcc\u4e0b1\u53f7\u7ebf\u7ad9\u53f0 \u8f7b\u8f68\u5b89\u5168\u95e8\u8fdf\u8fdf\u4e0d\u88c5 |author =\u5218\u5b5d\u658c\uff1b\u9ec4\u58eb\u5cf0 |date = 2016-01-06 |publisher=\u695a\u5929\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5}}</ref> The metro stations are equipped to be disabled and elderly friendly, with automatic fare collection system, announcement system, electronic display boards, escalators and lifts. The stations are equipped with non-slippery flooring with grip-rails, audio announcements and Braille facilities to help visually challenged passengers. \n\n===Gallery===\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|footer=\n|lines=2\n|width=200\n|height=150\n|align=center\n|File:Zhuyeshan Station 03.jpg|Station entrance\n|File:Guidepost of Wuhan Metro.jpg|Guidepost\n|File:\u4e2d\u5c71\u516c\u56ed.jpg|Zhongshan Park Station\n|File:Wuhan Business District Station 09.jpg|The hall of Wuhan Business District Station\n|File:Huangpu Road Station in 2017 (6).jpg|The hall of Huangpu Road Station, Line 8\n|File:Widened Platform of Wuhan Metro Line 1 Huangpu Road Station.jpg|Widened Platform of Huangpu Road Station, Line 1\n|File:Wuhan Metro Line 7 Pangxiejia Station Platform (2).jpg|Pangxiejia Station Platform, Line 7\n|File:Wangjiawan Station 02.jpg|The hall of Wangjiawan Station\n|File:Tianhe International Airport Station (Metro) 02.jpg|Tianhe International Airport Station\n|File:Xujiapeng Station (3).jpg|Xujiapeng Station platform, Line 8\n|File:Sanyang Rd. Station, Wuhan Metro Line 7 (2).jpg|Transfer passage at Sanyang Road Station\n|File:Hall of Matoutan Park Station.jpg|The hall of Matoutan Park Station\n|File:Hall of Luoxiong Road Station.jpg|The hall of Luoxiong Road Station\n|File:Hall of Hanzheng Street Station (1).jpg|The hall of Hanzheng Street Station\n|File:Platform of Hanzheng Street Station.jpg|The platform of Hanzheng Street Station\n|File:English zhongnan & hongguang.svg|Cross-platform transfer \n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Trams in Wuhan]]\n*[[Wuhan Metro Museum]]\n*[[List of rapid transit systems]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Wuhan Metro}}\n*[http://www.wuhanrt.com/ Official site] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[http://www.urbanrail.net/as/cn/wuhan/wuhan.htm UrbanRail.net's page on the Wuhan Metro]\n\n{{Hubei transit}}\n{{Rapid transit in the People's Republic of China}}\n\n[[Category:Wuhan Metro| ]]\n[[Category:Rapid transit in China]]\n[[Category:Underground rapid transit in China]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Projects established in 1979]]\n", "name_user": "Painjet", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImpact of 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on Wuhan Metro", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wuhan_Metro"}
{"title_page": "Loess", "text_new": "{{hatnote|This article is about the geologic material. For the statistical technique, see [[local regression]].<br>\"Yellow earth\" redirects here. For the film, see ''[[Yellow Earth]]''.}}\n{{short description|A predominantly silt-sized clastic sediment of accumulated wind-blown dust}}\n[[File:LoessVicksburg.jpg|thumb|Loess in [[Vicksburg, Mississippi]]]]\n\n'''Loess''' ({{IPAc-en|US|l|\u025b|s|,_|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|.|\u0259|s|,_|l|\u028c|s}}, {{IPAc-en|UK|l|\u025c|s}}; from [[German language|German]] ''L\u00f6ss'' {{IPA-de|l\u0153s|}}) is a [[clastic rock|clastic]], predominantly silt-sized sediment that is formed by the accumulation of wind-blown dust.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/> Ten percent of the Earth's land area is covered by loess or similar deposits.<ref name=\" VasiljevicEtAl2011\">{{cite journal | url=https://ojs.zrc-sazu.si/ags/article/viewFile/1328/1091 | title=Loess Towards (Geo) Tourism \u2013 Proposed Application on Loess in Vojvodina Region (North Serbia) | first=D. A. | last=Vasiljevic | first2=S. B. | last2=Markovic | first3=T. A. | last3=Hose | first4=I. | last4=Smalley | first5=K. | last5=O'Hara-Dhand | first6=B. | last6=Basarin | first7=T. | last7=Lukic | first8=M. D. | last8=Vujicic | journal=Acta geographica Slovenica | year=2011 | volume=51 | issue=2 | pages=390\u2013406 | doi=10.3986/AGS51305| doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nLoess is an [[aeolian processes|aeolian]] sediment formed by the accumulation of wind-blown [[silt]],<ref>Smalley, I. J., Derbyshire, E. 1990. \"The definition of 'ice-sheet' and 'mountain' loess\". Area 22, 300\u2013301</ref> typically in the 20\u201350 micrometer size range, twenty percent or less [[clay]] and the balance equal parts [[sand]] and silt<ref>Donahue, Miller, Shickluna (1977). Soils: An Introduction to Soils and Plant Growth, 4th edition. Prentice Hall</ref> that are loosely cemented by [[calcium carbonate]]. It is usually homogeneous and highly porous and is traversed by vertical capillaries that permit the sediment to fracture and form vertical bluffs.\n\nThe word ''loess'', with connotations of origin by wind-deposited accumulation, came into English from [[German language|German]] ''L\u00f6ss'', which can be traced back to [[Alemannic German|Swiss German]] and is [[cognate]] with the English word ''loose'' and the German word ''los''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=loess|title=loess |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref> It was first applied to Rhine River valley loess about 1821.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/346022/loess |title=loess (sedimentary deposit) |encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |accessdate=2013-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dwds.de/?qu=L%C3%B6ss&submit_button=Suche&view=1 |title=DWDS &#124; Suchergebnisse |publisher=Dwds.de |accessdate=2013-12-22}}</ref>\n\n==Properties==\n[[File:Loess landscape china.jpg|thumb|left|Loess near [[Hunyuan]], [[Datong]], [[Shanxi]] province, [[China]].]]\nLoess is [[wikt:homogeneous|homogeneous]], [[porous]], [[friable]], pale yellow or [[buff (color)|buff]], slightly [[wikt:coherent|coherent]], typically non-[[stratum|stratified]] and often [[calcareous]].  Loess grains are [[Rounding (sediment)|angular]] with little polishing or rounding and composed of crystals of [[quartz]], [[feldspar]], [[mica]] and other [[mineral]]s. Loess can be described as a rich, dust-like soil.<ref>Pearson Prentice Hall - World Studies - Europe and Russia</ref>\n\nLoess deposits may become very thick, more than a hundred meters in areas of China and tens of meters in parts of the Midwestern United States. It generally occurs as a blanket deposit that covers areas of hundreds of square kilometers and tens of meters thick.\n\nLoess often stands in either steep or vertical faces.<ref>Neuendorf, K.E.K., J.P. Mehl Jr., and J.A. Jackson, 2005, ''Glossary of Geology.'' [[Springer-Verlag]], [[New York City]], 779 pp., {{ISBN|3-540-27951-2}}</ref> Because the grains are angular, loess will often stand in banks for many years without [[Slump (geology)|slump]]ing. This soil has a characteristic called vertical cleavage which makes it easily excavated to form cave dwellings, a popular method of making [[yaodong|human habitations]] in some parts of China. Loess will erode very readily.\n\nIn several areas of the world, loess [[ridge]]s have formed that are aligned with the [[prevailing wind]]s during the last [[glacial maximum]].  These are called \"[[paha (landform)|paha]] ridges\" in America and \"greda ridges\" in [[Europe]].  The form of these loess [[dune]]s has been explained by a combination of wind and [[tundra]] conditions.\n\n==Etymology==\n''Loess'' comes from the German ''L\u00f6ss'' or ''L\u00f6\u00df'', and ultimately from [[Alemannic German|Alemannic]] ''l\u00f6sch'' meaning ''drop'' as named by [[peasants]] and [[masonry|mason]]s along the [[Rhine|Rhine Valley]].{{clarify|reason=does not agree with referenced material in lead|date=December 2018}}\n\n==History of research==\nThe term \"L\u00f6\u00df\" was first described in Central Europe by [[Karl C\u00e4sar von Leonhard]] (1823\u20131824)<ref>Leonhard K. C. von (1823\u20131824). ''Charakteristik der Felsarten''. 3 Vols., J. Engelmann Verlag Heidelberg, pp. 772.</ref> who reported yellowish brown, silty deposits along the Rhine valley near [[Heidelberg]].<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/> [[Charles Lyell]] (1834) brought this term into widespread usage by observing similarities between loess and loess derivatives along the loess bluffs in the Rhine and Mississippi.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\" /> At that time it was thought that the yellowish brown silt-rich sediment was of [[fluvial]] origin being deposited by the large rivers.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\" /> It wasn't until the end of the 19th century that the [[Aeolian processes|aeolian]] origin of loess was recognized (Virlet D'Aoust 1857),<ref>Virlet D'Aoust P.T. (1857). \"Observations sur un terrain d`origine m\u00e9t\u00e9orique ou de transport aerien qui existe au Mexique et sur le ph\u00e9nom\u00e8ne des trombes de poussi\u00e8re auquel il doit principalement son origine\". ''[[Geol. Soc. France, Full.]]'', 2d, Ser. 2, 129\u2013139.</ref> especially the convincing observations of loess in China by [[Ferdinand von Richthofen]] (1878).<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/><ref>Richthofen F. von (1878). \"Bemerkungen zur L\u00f6\u00dfbildung\". ''[[Verh Geol Reichsanst]]'', Berlin, pp 1\u201313.</ref> A tremendous number of papers have been published since then, focusing on the formation of loess and on loess/[[Paleosol|palaeosol]] (older soil buried under deposits) sequences as archives of climate and environment change.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/> These water conservation works were carried out extensively in China and the research of Loess in China has been continued since 1954. (Liu TS, Loess and the environment)\n\nMuch effort was put into the setting up of regional and local loess [[stratigraphy|stratigraphies]] and their correlation (Kukla 1970, 1975, 1977).<ref>Kukla G. (1970). \"Correlation between loesses and deep-sea sediments\". ''[[Geologiske Foreningen Foerhandlingar]]'' '''92''': 148\u2013180. Stockholm.</ref><ref>Kukla G. J. (1975). \"Loess stratigraphy of Central Europe\". In: Butzer K. W. & Isaac G. L. (eds.) After the Australopithecus, pp. 99\u2013188. Mouton, The Hague.</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kukla |first1=G. J. |year=1977 |title=Pleistocene Land-Sea Correlations I. Europe |journal=[[Earth-Science Reviews]] |volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=307\u2013374 |doi=10.1016/0012-8252(77)90125-8|bibcode=1977ESRv...13..307K }}</ref> But even the chronostratigraphical position of the last interglacial soil correlating to marine [[isotope]] substage 5e has been a matter of debate, owing to the lack of robust and reliable numerical dating, as summarized for example in Z\u00f6ller et al. (1994)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Z\u00f6ller |first1=L. |last2=Oches |first2=E. A. |last3=McCoy |first3=W. D. |year=1994 |title=Towards a revised chronostratigraphy of loess in Austria with respect to key sections in the Czech Republic and in Hungary |journal=[[Quaternary Geochronology]] |volume=13 |issue=5\u20137|pages=465\u2013472 |doi=10.1016/0277-3791(94)90059-0|bibcode=1994QSRv...13..465Z }}</ref> and Frechen, Horv\u00e1th & G\u00e1bris (1997)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Frechen |first1=M. |last2=Horv\u00e1th |first2=E. |last3=G\u00e1bris |first3=G. |year=1997 |title=Geochronology of Middle and Upper Pleistocene loess sections in Hungary |journal=[[Quaternary Research]] |volume=48 |issue=3 |pages=291\u2013312 |doi=10.1006/qres.1997.1929|bibcode=1997QuRes..48..291F }}</ref> for the Austrian and Hungarian loess stratigraphy,  respectively.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/>\n\nSince the 1980s, [[thermoluminescence]] (TL), [[optically stimulated luminescence]] (OSL) and infrared stimulated luminescence (IRSL) dating are available providing the possibility for dating the time of loess (dust) deposition, i.e. the time elapsed since the last exposure of the mineral grains to daylight.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\" /> During the past decade, [[luminescence dating]] has significantly improved by new methodological improvements, especially the development of single [[wikt:aliquot|aliquot]] regenerative (SAR) protocols (Murray & Wintle 2000)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Murray |first1=A. S. |last2=Wintle |first2=A. G. |year=2000 |title=Luminescence dating of quartz using an improved single aliquot regenerative-dose protocol |journal=[[Radiation Measurements (journal)|Radiation Measurements]] |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=57\u201373 |doi=10.1016/S1350-4487(99)00253-X|bibcode=2000RadM...32...57M }}</ref> resulting in reliable ages (or age estimates) with an accuracy of up to 5 and 10% for the [[last glacial]] record.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/> More recently, luminescence dating has also become a robust dating technique for penultimate and antepenultimate glacial loess (e.g. Thiel et al. 2011,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Thiel |first1=C. |last2=Buylaert |first2=J. P. |last3=Murray |first3=A. S. |last4=Terhorst |first4=B. |last5=Tsukamoto |first5=S. |last6=Frechen |first6=M. |last7=Sprafke |first7=T. |year=2011 |title=Investigating the chronostratigraphy of prominent palaeosols in Lower Austria using post-IR IRSL dating |journal=Quaternary Science Journal |volume=60 |issue=1|pages=137\u2013152 |doi=10.3285/eg.60.1.10|doi-access=free }}</ref> Schmidt et al. 2011)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schmidt |first1=E. D. |last2=Semmel |first2=A. |last3=Frechen |first3=M. |year=2011 |title=Luminescence dating of the loess/palaeosol sequence at the gravel quarry Gaul/Weilbach, Southern Hesse (Germany) |journal=Quaternary Science Journal |volume=60 |issue=1|pages=116\u2013125 |doi=10.3285/eg.60.1.08|doi-access=free }}</ref> allowing for a reliable correlation of loess/palaeosol sequences for at least the last two interglacial/glacial cycles throughout Europe and the Northern Hemisphere (Frechen 2011).<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Frechen|first1=M.|title=Loess in Eurasia|journal=Quaternary International|date=2011 |volume=234|issue=1\u20132|pages=1\u20133|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2010.11.014|bibcode=2011QuInt.234....1F}}</ref> Furthermore, the numerical dating provides the basis for quantitative loess research applying more sophisticated methods to determine and understand high-resolution proxy data, such as the palaeodust content of the atmosphere, variations of the atmospheric circulation patterns and wind systems, palaeoprecipitation and palaeotemperature.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\" />\n\nBesides luminescence dating methods, the use of radiocarbon dating in loess has increased during the past decades. Advances in methods of analyses, instrumentation and refinements to the radiocarbon calibration curve have enabled to obtain reliable ages from loess deposits for the last 40-45 ka. However, the use of this method relies on finding suitable in situ organic material in deposits such as charcoal, seeds, earthworm granules or snail shells.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00dajv\u00e1ri|first=G\u00e1bor|last2=Stevens|first2=Thomas|last3=Moln\u00e1r|first3=Mih\u00e1ly|last4=Dem\u00e9ny|first4=Attila|last5=Lambert|first5=Fabrice|last6=Varga|first6=Gy\u00f6rgy|last7=Jull|first7=A. J. Timothy|last8=P\u00e1ll-Gergely|first8=Barna|last9=Buylaert|first9=Jan-Pieter|last10=Kov\u00e1cs|first10=J\u00e1nos|date=2017-12-12|title=Coupled European and Greenland last glacial dust activity driven by North Atlantic climate|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=114|issue=50|pages=E10632\u2013E10638|doi=10.1073/pnas.1712651114|issn=0027-8424|pmc=5740632|pmid=29180406|bibcode=2017PNAS..11410632U}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moine|first=Olivier|last2=Antoine|first2=Pierre|last3=Hatt\u00e9|first3=Christine|last4=Landais|first4=Ama\u00eblle|last5=Mathieu|first5=J\u00e9r\u00f4me|last6=Prud\u2019homme|first6=Charlotte|last7=Rousseau|first7=Denis-Didier|date=2017-06-13|title=The impact of Last Glacial climate variability in west-European loess revealed by radiocarbon dating of fossil earthworm granules|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=114|issue=24|pages=6209\u20136214|doi=10.1073/pnas.1614751114|issn=0027-8424|pmc=5474771|pmid=28559353|bibcode=2017PNAS..114.6209M}}</ref>\n\n==Formation==\nAccording to Pye (1995),<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pye | first1 = K | year = 1995 | title = The nature, origin and accumulation of loess | url = | journal = [[Quaternary Science Reviews]] | volume = 14 | issue = 7\u20138| pages = 653\u2013667 | doi=10.1016/0277-3791(95)00047-x| bibcode = 1995QSRv...14..653P}}</ref> four fundamental requirements are necessary for the formation of loess: a dust source, adequate wind energy to transport the dust, a suitable accumulation area, and a sufficient amount of time.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/>\n\n===Periglacial loess===\n[[Periglacial]] (glacial) loess is derived from the floodplains of [[glacier|glacial]] [[braided river]]s that carried large volumes of glacial meltwater and sediments from the annual melting of continental icesheets and mountain icecaps during the spring and summer. During the autumn and winter, when melting of the icesheets and icecaps ceased, the flow of meltwater down these rivers either ceased or was greatly reduced. As a consequence, large parts of the formerly submerged and unvegetated floodplains of these braided rivers dried out and were exposed to the wind. Because these floodplains consist of sediment containing a high content of glacially ground flour-like [[silt]] and [[clay]], they were highly susceptible to winnowing of their silts and [[clay]]s by the wind. Once entrained by the wind, particles were then deposited downwind. The loess deposits found along both sides of the [[Mississippi embayment|Mississippi River Alluvial Valley]] are a classic example of periglacial loess.<ref name=\"MuhsOthers2003a\">{{cite journal|last1=Bettis|first1=E.A.|last2=Muhs|first2=D.R.|last3=Roberts|first3=H.M.|last4=Wintle|first4=A.G.|title=Last Glacial loess in the conterminous USA|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|date=2003|volume=22|issue=18\u201319|pages=1907\u20131946|doi=10.1016/S0277-3791(03)00169-0|bibcode=2003QSRv...22.1907A}}</ref><ref name=\"esp.cr.usgs.gov\">{{cite journal|last1=Muhs|first1= D.R.|first2=E.A. |last2=Bettis, III|date=2003|url=http://esp.cr.usgs.gov/info/eolian/MuhsBettis2003GSAsp370.pdf |title=Quaternary loess-paleosol sequences as examples of climate-driven sedimentary extremes|journal=GSA Special Papers|volume=370|pages= 53\u201374|doi=10.1130/0-8137-2370-1.53|isbn= 9780813723709}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Quaternary]], loess and loess-like sediments were formed in periglacial environments on mid-continental [[Shield (geology)|shield]] areas in Europe and Siberia, on the margins of high mountain ranges like in [[Tajikistan]] and on semi-arid margins of some lowland deserts like in China.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/>\n\nIn England, periglacial loess is also known as [[brickearth]].\n\n===Non-glacial===\nNon-glacial loess can originate from [[desert]]s, [[dune field]]s, [[playa lake]]s, and [[volcanic ash]].\n\nSome types of nonglacial loess are:<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Iriondo | first1 = M.H. | last2 = Krohling | first2 = D.M. | year = 2007 | title = Non-classical types of loess | journal = [[Sedimentary Geology (journal)|Sedimentary Geology]] | volume = 202 | issue = 3| pages = 352\u2013368 | bibcode=2007SedG..202..352I | doi=10.1016/j.sedgeo.2007.03.012}}</ref>\n* [[Desert]] loess produced by aeolian attrition of quartz grains <ref>Whalley, W.B., Marshall, J.R., Smith, B.J. 1982, Origin of desert loess from some experimental observations, Nature, 300, 433-435.</ref> \n* [[Volcanic]] loess in Ecuador and Argentina;\n* [[Tropical]] loess in Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay;\n* [[Gypsum]] loess in Spain;\n* [[Trade wind]] loess in Venezuela and Brazil;\n* [[Anticyclonic]] loess in Argentina.\n\nThe thick Chinese loess deposits are non-glacial loess having been blown in from deserts in northern China.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Ding | first1 = Z. | last2 = Sun | first2 = J. | year = 1999 | title = Changes in Sand Content of Loess Deposits along a North\u2013South Transect of the Chinese Loess Plateau and the Implications for Desert Variations. | url = | journal = [[Quaternary Research]] | volume = 52 | issue = 1| pages = 56\u201362 | doi=10.1006/qres.1999.2045| bibcode = 1999QuRes..52...56D }}</ref> The loess covering the [[Great Plains]] of [[Nebraska]], [[Kansas]], and [[Colorado]] is considered to be non-glacial desert loess.<ref name=\"MuhsOthers2003a\"/> Non-glacial desert loess is also found in Australia<ref>{{cite journal|last=Haberlah|first=D|year=2007|title=A call for Australian loess|journal=Area |volume=39 |issue=2|pages= 224\u2013229|doi=10.1111/j.1475-4762.2007.00730.x}}</ref> and Africa.<ref name=\"esp.cr.usgs.gov\"/>\n\n==Fertility==\nLoess tends to develop into very rich soils. Under appropriate climatic conditions, it is some of the most agriculturally productive terrain in the world.<ref>{{cite book|last=Getis|first=Arthur|author2=Judith Getis and Jerome D. Fellmann|title=Introduction to Geography, Seventh Edition|year=2000|publisher=[[McGraw Hill]]|isbn=0-697-38506-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/introductiontoge00geti/page/99 99]|url=https://archive.org/details/introductiontoge00geti/page/99}}</ref>\n\nSoils underlain by loess tend to be excessively drained. The fine grains [[weathering|weather]] rapidly due to their large surface area, making soils derived from loess rich.  One theory states that the fertility of loess soils is due largely to [[cation exchange capacity]] (the ability of plants to absorb nutrients from the soil) and [[porosity]] (the air-filled space in the soil). The fertility of loess is not due to organic matter content, which tends to be rather low, unlike tropical soils which derive their fertility almost wholly from organic matter.\n\nEven well managed loess [[arable land|farmland]] can experience dramatic [[erosion]] of well over 2.5&nbsp;kg /m<sup>2</sup> per year. In China the [[Loess Plateau|loess deposits]] which give the [[Yellow River]] its color have been farmed and have produced phenomenal yields for over one thousand years. Winds pick up loess particles, contributing to the [[Asian Dust]] pollution problem. The largest deposit of loess in the United States, the [[Loess Hills]] along the border of [[Iowa]] and Nebraska, has survived intensive farming and [[Land degradation|poor farming practices]]. For almost 150 years, this loess deposit was farmed with [[mouldboard plough]]s and fall tilled, both intensely erosive. At times it suffered erosion rates of over 10 kilograms per square meter per year. Today this loess deposit is worked as low till or [[no till]] in all areas and is aggressively [[terrace (agriculture)|terraced]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n==Large areas of loess deposits and soils==\n===Argentina===\n[[File:ArgentinaLoess.JPG|right|thumb|An [[outcrop]] of loess in [[Patagonia]]]]\nMuch of Argentina is covered by loess. Two areas of loess are usually distinguished in Argentina: the neotropical loess north of [[30th parallel south|latitude 30\u00b0 S]] and the pampean loess.<ref name=Sagayo/>\n\nThe neotropical loess is made of silt or silty clay. Relative to the pampean loess the neotropical loess is poor in [[quartz]] and [[calcium carbonate]]. The source region for this loess is thought by some scientists to be areas of [[fluvio-glacial]] deposits the Andean foothills formed by the [[Patagonian Ice Sheet]]. Other researchers stress the importance of [[tephra|volcanic material]] in the neotropical loess.<ref name=Sagayo/>\n\nThe pampean loess is sandy or made of silty sand.<ref name=Sagayo>{{cite journal |last=Sagayo |first=Jos\u00e9 Manuel |date=1995 |title=The Argentine neotropical loess: An overview |url= |journal=Quaternary Science Reviews |publisher=Pergamon |volume=14 |issue=7\u20138 |pages=755\u2013766 |doi=10.1016/0277-3791(95)00050-X |bibcode=1995QSRv...14..755S }}</ref>\n\n=== Central Asia ===\nFrom Southern Tajikistan up to Almaty, Kazakhstan, spans an area of multiple loess deposits.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ding |first=Z.L. |date=2002 |title=The loess record in southern Tajikistan and correlation with Chinese loess |url= |journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters |publisher=Elsevier |volume=200 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=387\u2013400|doi=10.1016/S0012-821X(02)00637-4 |bibcode=2002E&PSL.200..387D }}, Fig. 1 (b) showing the distribution of loess, deserts, and mountains in Central Asia (adopted from [T.S. Liu, Loess and the Environment, China Ocean Press, Beijing, 1985.]). The locality of the Chashmanigar loess section is indicated by the solid arrow.</ref>\n\n===China===\nThe [[Loess Plateau]] (simplified Chinese: \u9ec4\u571f\u9ad8\u539f; traditional Chinese: \u9ec3\u571f\u9ad8\u539f; pinyin: hu\u00e1ngt\u01d4 g\u0101oyu\u00e1n), also known as the Huangtu Plateau, is a [[plateau]] that covers an area of some 640,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> in the upper and middle of [[China]]'s [[Yellow River]] and China proper.  The Yellow River was so named because the loess forming its banks gave a yellowish tint to the water.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Huang He |url=http://www.bartleby.com/65/hu/HuangHe.html |encyclopedia=[[The Columbia Encyclopedia]] |edition=6th |year=2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605050404/http://www.bartleby.com/65/hu/HuangHe.html |archivedate=June 5, 2009 }}</ref> The soil of this region has been called the \"most highly erodible soil on earth\".<ref>John M. Laflen, Soil Erosion and Dryland Farming, 2000, CRC Press, 736 pages {{ISBN|0-8493-2349-5}}</ref> The Loess Plateau and its dusty [[soil]] cover almost all of [[Shanxi]], [[Shaanxi]], and [[Gansu]] provinces, the [[Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region]], and parts of others.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n===New Zealand===\nExtensive areas of loess occur in New Zealand including the [[Canterbury Plains]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/canterbury-region/page-3|title=Canterbury Region|publisher= Encyclopedia of New Zealand|author=John Wilson|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> and on the [[Banks Peninsula]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Eileen McSaveney|title= Glaciers and glaciation - Retreating ice and the glacier legacy|publisher= Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/photograph/10750/loess-deposits-banks-peninsula|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> <ref>Smalley, I.J., Davin, J.E. 1980. The First Hundred Years-A Historical Bibliography of New Zealand Loess. New Zealand Soil Bureau Bibliographic Report 28, 166pp.</ref> The basis of loess stratigraphy was introduced by [[John Hardcastle]] in 1890 <ref>*Hardcastle, J. 1890. On the Timaru loess as a climate register. Transcations & Proceedings of the New Zealand Institute 23, 324-332 (on line: Royal Society of New Zealand http://rsnz.natlib.govt.nz; reproduced in Loess Letter supplement 23, November 1988).</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[File:Distribution of loess in North America.gif|thumb|Map showing the distribution of loess in United States.<ref name=\"usgs muhs\">{{cite web |author= Muhs|title=Eolian History of North America: Task 2, Understand the paleoclimatic significance of loess |url= http://gec.cr.usgs.gov/archive/eolian/task2.shtml |publisher= [[USGS]] |date= 2013-02-06|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130218195902/http://gec.cr.usgs.gov/archive/eolian/task2.shtml |archive-date= 2013-02-18 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>]]\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2016}}\nThe [[Loess Hills]] of Iowa owe their fertility to the [[prairie]] [[topsoil]]s built by 10,000 years of post-glacial accumulation of organic-rich [[humus]] as a consequence of a persistent [[grassland]] [[biome]]. When the valuable [[A horizon|A-horizon]] topsoil is eroded or degraded, the underlying loess soil is infertile, and requires the addition of [[fertilizer]] in order to support [[agriculture]].\n\nThe loess along the [[Mississippi River]] near [[Vicksburg, Mississippi|Vicksburg]], [[Mississippi]], consist of three layers. The ''Peoria Loess'', ''Sicily Island Loess'', and ''Crowley's Ridge Loess'' accumulated at different periods of time during the [[Pleistocene]]. Ancient soils, called [[paleosol]]s, have developed in the top of the Sicily Island Loess and Crowley's Ridge Loess. The lowermost loess, the Crowley's Ridge Loess, accumulated during the late [[Illinoian (stage)|Illinoian Stage]]. The middle loess, Sicily Island Loess, accumulated during early [[Wisconsin glaciation|Wisconsin Stage]]. The uppermost loess, the Peoria Loess, in which the modern soil has developed, accumulated during the late Wisconsin Stage. Animal remains include terrestrial [[gastropod]]s and [[mastodon]]s.<ref name=\"MillerOthers1\">Miller, B.J., G.C. Lewis, J.J. Alford, and W.J. Day, 1985, [https://www.scribd.com/doc/18934817/1984-Louisiana-Loess-Fieldtrip-Guidebook ''Loesses in Louisiana and at Vicksburg, Mississippi. Guidebook, Friends of the Pleistocene Field Trip, 12-14 April, 1985.''] [[LA Agricultural Experimental Station]], [[Louisiana State University]], [[Baton Rouge]], [[Louisiana]]. 126 pp.</ref>\n\n=== Europe ===\nLoess deposits of varying thickness (decimeter to several tens of meters) are widely distributed over the European continent.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Schaetzl|first=Randall J.|last2=Bettis|first2=E. Arthur|last3=Crouvi|first3=Onn|last4=Fitzsimmons|first4=Kathryn E.|last5=Grimley|first5=David A.|last6=Hambach|first6=Ulrich|last7=Lehmkuhl|first7=Frank|last8=Markovi\u0107|first8=Slobodan B.|last9=Mason|first9=Joseph A.|last10=Owczarek|first10=Piotr|last11=Roberts|first11=Helen M.|date=May 2018|title=Approaches and challenges to the study of loess\u2014Introduction to the LoessFest Special Issue|journal=Quaternary Research|volume=89|issue=3|pages=563\u2013618|doi=10.1017/qua.2018.15|issn=0033-5894|bibcode=2018QuRes..89..563S|doi-access=free}}</ref> The northern European loess belt stretches fromsouthern England and northern [[France]] to [[Germany]], [[Poland]] and the southern [[Ukraine]] and deposits are characterized by strong influences of [[periglacial]] conditions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vandenberghe|first=Jef|last2=French|first2=Hugh M.|last3=Gorbunov|first3=Aldar|last4=Marchenko|first4=Sergei|last5=Velichko|first5=Andrey A.|last6=Jin|first6=Huijun|last7=Cui|first7=Zhijiu|last8=Zhang|first8=Tingjun|last9=Wan|first9=Xudong|date=2014|title=The Last Permafrost Maximum (LPM) map of the Northern Hemisphere: permafrost extent and mean annual air temperatures, 25\u201317 ka BP|journal=Boreas|volume=43|issue=3|pages=652\u2013666|doi=10.1111/bor.12070|issn=1502-3885}}</ref> South-eastern European loess is mainly deposited in plateau-like situations in the [[Danube basin]]s, likely derived from the Danube River system.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fitzsimmons|first=Kathryn E.|last2=Markovi\u0107|first2=Slobodan B.|last3=Hambach|first3=Ulrich|date=2012-05-18|title=Pleistocene environmental dynamics recorded in the loess of the middle and lower Danube basin|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|volume=41|pages=104\u2013118|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2012.03.002|issn=0277-3791|bibcode=2012QSRv...41..104F}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jipa|first=Dan C.|date=November 2014|title=The conceptual sedimentary model of the Lower Danube loess basin: Sedimentogenetic implications|journal=Quaternary International|volume=351|pages=14\u201324|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2013.06.008|issn=1040-6182|bibcode=2014QuInt.351...14J}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00dajv\u00e1ri|first=G\u00e1bor|last2=Varga|first2=Andrea|last3=Ramos|first3=Frank C.|last4=Kov\u00e1cs|first4=J\u00e1nos|last5=N\u00e9meth|first5=Tibor|last6=Stevens|first6=Thomas|date=April 2012|title=Evaluating the use of clay mineralogy, Sr\u2013Nd isotopes and zircon U\u2013Pb ages in tracking dust provenance: An example from loess of the Carpathian Basin|journal=Chemical Geology|volume=304-305|pages=83\u201396|doi=10.1016/j.chemgeo.2012.02.007|issn=0009-2541|bibcode=2012ChGeo.304...83U}}</ref> In south-western Europe, relocated loess derivatives are mostly restricted to the [[Ebro Valley]] and central [[Spain]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boixadera|first=Jaume|last2=Poch|first2=Rosa M.|last3=Lowick|first3=Sally E.|last4=Balasch|first4=J. Carles|date=July 2015|title=Loess and soils in the eastern Ebro Basin|journal=Quaternary International|volume=376|pages=114\u2013133|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2014.07.046|issn=1040-6182|bibcode=2015QuInt.376..114B}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bertran|first=Pascal|last2=Liard|first2=Morgane|last3=Sitzia|first3=Luca|last4=Tissoux|first4=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|date=November 2016|title=A map of Pleistocene aeolian deposits in Western Europe, with special emphasis on France|journal=Journal of Quaternary Science|volume=31|issue=8|pages=e2909|doi=10.1002/jqs.2909|issn=0267-8179|bibcode=2016JQS....31E2909B}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{annotated link|B\u00f6rde}} \u2013 North German loess regions\n* {{annotated link|G\u00e4u|G\u00e4ue}} \u2013 South German loess regions\n* {{annotated link|Loam}}\n\n==References==\nThis article incorporates CC-BY-3.0 text from the reference<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\">{{cite journal | last1 = Frechen | first1 = M | year = 2011 | title = Loess in Europe | url = | journal = Quaternary Science Journal | volume = 60 | issue = 1| pages = 3\u20135 | doi = 10.3285/eg.60.1.00 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Smalley, I. J. (editor) 1975. ''Loess Lithology & Genesis''. Benchmark Geology 26. Dowden, Hutchinson & Ross 454pp.\n* Smalley, I. J. 1980.  ''Loess: A Partial Bibliography''.  Geobooks/Elsevier. {{ISBN|0 86094 036 5}}. 103pp.\n* Rozycki, S. Z. 1991. ''Loess and Loess-like Deposits''. Ossolineum Wroclaw {{ISBN|83-04-03745-9}}. 187pp.\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|loess}}\n{{commons category|Loess}}\n{{Americana Poster}}\n* 2006, [http://www.semp.us/publications/biot_printview.php?BiotID=357 ''The Secret of China\u2019s Vast Loess Plateau''] [[Suburban Emergency Management Project]], Chicago, Illinois.\n* 2007, [http://www.ufz.de/index.php?en=15536 ''New European Loess Map.''] [[Helmholtz Centre for Environmental Research]], [[Leipzig]], Germany.\n* [http://www.museum.state.il.us/exhibits/larson/loess.html ''Glacial Deposits: Loess and Till.''] [[Illinois State Museum]], [[Springfield, Illinois]].\n* Briedis. C.A., 2006, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080905190943/http://www.isgs.uiuc.edu/sections/quat/loessthick-map.shtml ''Loess Thickness Map (of Illinois).''] [[Illinois State Geological Survey]], [[Champaign, Illinois]].\n* [https://www.lbk.ars.usda.gov/wewc/biblio/bar.htm The Bibliography of Aeolian Research]\n* Heinrich, P.V., 2008, [https://web.archive.org/web/20090325233831/http://www.lgs.lsu.edu/deploy/uploads/Loess%20Map%20of%20LA.pdf ''Loess map of Louisiana.''], Public Information Series. no. 12, [[Louisiana Geological Survey]], [[Baton Rouge]], [[Louisiana]].\n* Prior, J.C., and D.J. Quade, nd, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080521133019/http://www.igsb.uiowa.edu/browse/loess/loess.htm ''The Loess Hills: A Geologic View.''] [[Iowa Geological Survey]], [[Iowa Department of Natural Resources|Department of Natural Resources]], [[Iowa City]], Iowa.\n* [[U.S. Geological Survey]], 1999, [http://pubs.usgs.gov/info/loess/ ''Geology of the Loess Hills, Iowa'']\n* [[U.S. Geological Survey]], 2006, [http://esp.cr.usgs.gov/info/eolian/task2.html ''Eolian History of North America''] Why is loess important to study?\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080626123416/http://www.nfinity.com/~exile/loesspg.htm ''The Loess Hills of Western Iowa'']\n* [http://www.mojeroztocze.pl/index.php/galeria?func=viewcategory&catid=3 ''The Loess Hills of Roztocze in Poland'']\n\n{{soil type}}\n{{Geotechnical engineering}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Pedology]]\n[[Category:Glaciology]]\n[[Category:Sedimentary rocks]]\n[[Category:Sediments]]\n[[Category:Types of soil]]\n[[Category:Aeolian landforms]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|This article is about the geologic material. For the statistical technique, see [[local regression]].<br>\"Yellow earth\" redirects here. For the film, see ''[[Yellow Earth]]''.}}\n{{short description|A predominantly silt-sized clastic sediment of accumulated wind-blown dust}}\n[[File:LoessVicksburg.jpg|thumb|Loess in [[Vicksburg, Mississippi]]]]\n\n'''Loess''' ({{IPAc-en|US|l|\u025b|s|,_|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|.|\u0259|s|,_|l|\u028c|s}}, {{IPAc-en|UK|l|\u025c|s}}; from [[German language|German]] ''L\u00f6ss'' {{IPA-de|l\u0153s|}}) is a [[clastic rock|clastic]], predominantly silt-sized sediment that is formed by the accumulation of wind-blown dust.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/> Ten percent of the Earth's land area is covered by loess or similar deposits.<ref name=\" VasiljevicEtAl2011\">{{cite journal | url=https://ojs.zrc-sazu.si/ags/article/viewFile/1328/1091 | title=Loess Towards (Geo) Tourism \u2013 Proposed Application on Loess in Vojvodina Region (North Serbia) | first=D. A. | last=Vasiljevic | first2=S. B. | last2=Markovic | first3=T. A. | last3=Hose | first4=I. | last4=Smalley | first5=K. | last5=O'Hara-Dhand | first6=B. | last6=Basarin | first7=T. | last7=Lukic | first8=M. D. | last8=Vujicic | journal=Acta geographica Slovenica | year=2011 | volume=51 | issue=2 | pages=390\u2013406 | doi=10.3986/AGS51305| doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nLoess is an [[aeolian processes|aeolian]] sediment formed by the accumulation of wind-blown [[silt]],<ref>Smalley, I. J., Derbyshire, E. 1990. \"The definition of 'ice-sheet' and 'mountain' loess\". Area 22, 300\u2013301</ref> typically in the 20\u201350 micrometer size range, twenty percent or less [[clay]] and the balance equal parts [[sand]] and silt<ref>Donahue, Miller, Shickluna (1977). Soils: An Introduction to Soils and Plant Growth, 4th edition. Prentice Hall</ref> that are loosely cemented by [[calcium carbonate]]. It is usually homogeneous and highly porous and is traversed by vertical capillaries that permit the sediment to fracture and form vertical bluffs.\n\nThe word ''loess'', with connotations of origin by wind-deposited accumulation, came into English from [[German language|German]] ''L\u00f6ss'', which can be traced back to [[Alemannic German|Swiss German]] and is [[cognate]] with the English word ''loose'' and the German word ''los''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=loess|title=loess |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref> It was first applied to Rhine River valley loess about 1821.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/346022/loess |title=loess (sedimentary deposit) |encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |accessdate=2013-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dwds.de/?qu=L%C3%B6ss&submit_button=Suche&view=1 |title=DWDS &#124; Suchergebnisse |publisher=Dwds.de |accessdate=2013-12-22}}</ref>\n\n==Properties==\n[[File:Loess landscape china.jpg|thumb|left|Loess near [[Hunyuan]], [[Datong]], [[Shanxi]] province, [[China]].]]\nLoess is [[wikt:homogeneous|homogeneous]], [[porous]], [[friable]], pale yellow or [[buff (color)|buff]], slightly [[wikt:coherent|coherent]], typically non-[[stratum|stratified]] and often [[calcareous]].  Loess grains are [[Rounding (sediment)|angular]] with little polishing or rounding and composed of crystals of [[quartz]], [[feldspar]], [[mica]] and other [[mineral]]s. Loess can be described as a rich, dust-like soil.<ref>Pearson Prentice Hall - World Studies - Europe and Russia</ref>\n\nLoess deposits may become very thick, more than a hundred meters in areas of China and tens of meters in parts of the Midwestern United States. It generally occurs as a blanket deposit that covers areas of hundreds of square kilometers and tens of meters thick.\n\nLoess often stands in either steep or vertical faces.<ref>Neuendorf, K.E.K., J.P. Mehl Jr., and J.A. Jackson, 2005, ''Glossary of Geology.'' [[Springer-Verlag]], [[New York City]], 779 pp., {{ISBN|3-540-27951-2}}</ref> Because the grains are angular, loess will often stand in banks for many years without [[Slump (geology)|slump]]ing. This soil has a characteristic called vertical cleavage which makes it easily excavated to form cave dwellings, a popular method of making [[yaodong|human habitations]] in some parts of China. Loess will erode very readily.\n\nIn several areas of the world, loess [[ridge]]s have formed that are aligned with the [[prevailing wind]]s during the last [[glacial maximum]].  These are called \"[[paha (landform)|paha]] ridges\" in America and \"greda ridges\" in [[Europe]].  The form of these loess [[dune]]s has been explained by a combination of wind and [[tundra]] conditions.\n\n==Etymology==\n''Loess'' comes from the German ''L\u00f6ss'' or ''L\u00f6\u00df'', and ultimately from [[Alemannic German|Alemannic]] ''l\u00f6sch'' meaning ''drop'' as named by [[peasants]] and [[masonry|mason]]s along the [[Rhine|Rhine Valley]].{{clarify|reason=does not agree with referenced material in lead|date=December 2018}}\n\n==History of research==\nThe term \"L\u00f6\u00df\" was first described in Central Europe by [[Karl C\u00e4sar von Leonhard]] (1823\u20131824)<ref>Leonhard K. C. von (1823\u20131824). ''Charakteristik der Felsarten''. 3 Vols., J. Engelmann Verlag Heidelberg, pp. 772.</ref> who reported yellowish brown, silty deposits along the Rhine valley near [[Heidelberg]].<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/> [[Charles Lyell]] (1834) brought this term into widespread usage by observing similarities between loess and loess derivatives along the loess bluffs in the Rhine and Mississippi.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\" /> At that time it was thought that the yellowish brown silt-rich sediment was of [[fluvial]] origin being deposited by the large rivers.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\" /> It wasn't until the end of the 19th century that the [[Aeolian processes|aeolian]] origin of loess was recognized (Virlet D'Aoust 1857),<ref>Virlet D'Aoust P.T. (1857). \"Observations sur un terrain d`origine m\u00e9t\u00e9orique ou de transport aerien qui existe au Mexique et sur le ph\u00e9nom\u00e8ne des trombes de poussi\u00e8re auquel il doit principalement son origine\". ''[[Geol. Soc. France, Full.]]'', 2d, Ser. 2, 129\u2013139.</ref> especially the convincing observations of loess in China by [[Ferdinand von Richthofen]] (1878).<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/><ref>Richthofen F. von (1878). \"Bemerkungen zur L\u00f6\u00dfbildung\". ''[[Verh Geol Reichsanst]]'', Berlin, pp 1\u201313.</ref> A tremendous number of papers have been published since then, focusing on the formation of loess and on loess/[[Paleosol|palaeosol]] (older soil buried under deposits) sequences as archives of climate and environment change.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/> These water conservation works were carried out extensively in China and the research of Loess in China has been continued since 1954. (Liu TS, Loess and the environment)\n\nMuch effort was put into the setting up of regional and local loess [[stratigraphy|stratigraphies]] and their correlation (Kukla 1970, 1975, 1977).<ref>Kukla G. (1970). \"Correlation between loesses and deep-sea sediments\". ''[[Geologiske Foreningen Foerhandlingar]]'' '''92''': 148\u2013180. Stockholm.</ref><ref>Kukla G. J. (1975). \"Loess stratigraphy of Central Europe\". In: Butzer K. W. & Isaac G. L. (eds.) After the Australopithecus, pp. 99\u2013188. Mouton, The Hague.</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kukla |first1=G. J. |year=1977 |title=Pleistocene Land-Sea Correlations I. Europe |journal=[[Earth-Science Reviews]] |volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=307\u2013374 |doi=10.1016/0012-8252(77)90125-8|bibcode=1977ESRv...13..307K }}</ref> But even the chronostratigraphical position of the last interglacial soil correlating to marine [[isotope]] substage 5e has been a matter of debate, owing to the lack of robust and reliable numerical dating, as summarized for example in Z\u00f6ller et al. (1994)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Z\u00f6ller |first1=L. |last2=Oches |first2=E. A. |last3=McCoy |first3=W. D. |year=1994 |title=Towards a revised chronostratigraphy of loess in Austria with respect to key sections in the Czech Republic and in Hungary |journal=[[Quaternary Geochronology]] |volume=13 |issue=5\u20137|pages=465\u2013472 |doi=10.1016/0277-3791(94)90059-0|bibcode=1994QSRv...13..465Z }}</ref> and Frechen, Horv\u00e1th & G\u00e1bris (1997)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Frechen |first1=M. |last2=Horv\u00e1th |first2=E. |last3=G\u00e1bris |first3=G. |year=1997 |title=Geochronology of Middle and Upper Pleistocene loess sections in Hungary |journal=[[Quaternary Research]] |volume=48 |issue=3 |pages=291\u2013312 |doi=10.1006/qres.1997.1929|bibcode=1997QuRes..48..291F }}</ref> for the Austrian and Hungarian loess stratigraphy,  respectively.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/>\n\nSince the 1980s, [[thermoluminescence]] (TL), [[optically stimulated luminescence]] (OSL) and infrared stimulated luminescence (IRSL) dating are available providing the possibility for dating the time of loess (dust) deposition, i.e. the time elapsed since the last exposure of the mineral grains to daylight.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\" /> During the past decade, [[luminescence dating]] has significantly improved by new methodological improvements, especially the development of single [[wikt:aliquot|aliquot]] regenerative (SAR) protocols (Murray & Wintle 2000)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Murray |first1=A. S. |last2=Wintle |first2=A. G. |year=2000 |title=Luminescence dating of quartz using an improved single aliquot regenerative-dose protocol |journal=[[Radiation Measurements (journal)|Radiation Measurements]] |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=57\u201373 |doi=10.1016/S1350-4487(99)00253-X|bibcode=2000RadM...32...57M }}</ref> resulting in reliable ages (or age estimates) with an accuracy of up to 5 and 10% for the [[last glacial]] record.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/> More recently, luminescence dating has also become a robust dating technique for penultimate and antepenultimate glacial loess (e.g. Thiel et al. 2011,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Thiel |first1=C. |last2=Buylaert |first2=J. P. |last3=Murray |first3=A. S. |last4=Terhorst |first4=B. |last5=Tsukamoto |first5=S. |last6=Frechen |first6=M. |last7=Sprafke |first7=T. |year=2011 |title=Investigating the chronostratigraphy of prominent palaeosols in Lower Austria using post-IR IRSL dating |journal=Quaternary Science Journal |volume=60 |issue=1|pages=137\u2013152 |doi=10.3285/eg.60.1.10|doi-access=free }}</ref> Schmidt et al. 2011)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schmidt |first1=E. D. |last2=Semmel |first2=A. |last3=Frechen |first3=M. |year=2011 |title=Luminescence dating of the loess/palaeosol sequence at the gravel quarry Gaul/Weilbach, Southern Hesse (Germany) |journal=Quaternary Science Journal |volume=60 |issue=1|pages=116\u2013125 |doi=10.3285/eg.60.1.08|doi-access=free }}</ref> allowing for a reliable correlation of loess/palaeosol sequences for at least the last two interglacial/glacial cycles throughout Europe and the Northern Hemisphere (Frechen 2011).<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Frechen|first1=M.|title=Loess in Eurasia|journal=Quaternary International|date=2011 |volume=234|issue=1\u20132|pages=1\u20133|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2010.11.014|bibcode=2011QuInt.234....1F}}</ref> Furthermore, the numerical dating provides the basis for quantitative loess research applying more sophisticated methods to determine and understand high-resolution proxy data, such as the palaeodust content of the atmosphere, variations of the atmospheric circulation patterns and wind systems, palaeoprecipitation and palaeotemperature.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\" />\n\nBesides luminescence dating methods, the use of radiocarbon dating in loess has increased during the past decades. Advances in methods of analyses, instrumentation and refinements to the radiocarbon calibration curve have enabled to obtain reliable ages from loess deposits for the last 40-45 ka. However, the use of this method relies on finding suitable in situ organic material in deposits such as charcoal, seeds, earthworm granules or snail shells.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00dajv\u00e1ri|first=G\u00e1bor|last2=Stevens|first2=Thomas|last3=Moln\u00e1r|first3=Mih\u00e1ly|last4=Dem\u00e9ny|first4=Attila|last5=Lambert|first5=Fabrice|last6=Varga|first6=Gy\u00f6rgy|last7=Jull|first7=A. J. Timothy|last8=P\u00e1ll-Gergely|first8=Barna|last9=Buylaert|first9=Jan-Pieter|last10=Kov\u00e1cs|first10=J\u00e1nos|date=2017-12-12|title=Coupled European and Greenland last glacial dust activity driven by North Atlantic climate|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=114|issue=50|pages=E10632\u2013E10638|doi=10.1073/pnas.1712651114|issn=0027-8424|pmc=5740632|pmid=29180406|bibcode=2017PNAS..11410632U}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moine|first=Olivier|last2=Antoine|first2=Pierre|last3=Hatt\u00e9|first3=Christine|last4=Landais|first4=Ama\u00eblle|last5=Mathieu|first5=J\u00e9r\u00f4me|last6=Prud\u2019homme|first6=Charlotte|last7=Rousseau|first7=Denis-Didier|date=2017-06-13|title=The impact of Last Glacial climate variability in west-European loess revealed by radiocarbon dating of fossil earthworm granules|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=114|issue=24|pages=6209\u20136214|doi=10.1073/pnas.1614751114|issn=0027-8424|pmc=5474771|pmid=28559353|bibcode=2017PNAS..114.6209M}}</ref>\n\n==Formation==\nAccording to Pye (1995),<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pye | first1 = K | year = 1995 | title = The nature, origin and accumulation of loess | url = | journal = [[Quaternary Science Reviews]] | volume = 14 | issue = 7\u20138| pages = 653\u2013667 | doi=10.1016/0277-3791(95)00047-x| bibcode = 1995QSRv...14..653P}}</ref> four fundamental requirements are necessary for the formation of loess: a dust source, adequate wind energy to transport the dust, a suitable accumulation area, and a sufficient amount of time.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/>\n\n===Periglacial loess===\n[[Periglacial]] (glacial) loess is derived from the floodplains of [[glacier|glacial]] [[braided river]]s that carried large volumes of glacial meltwater and sediments from the annual melting of continental icesheets and mountain icecaps during the spring and summer. During the autumn and winter, when melting of the icesheets and icecaps ceased, the flow of meltwater down these rivers either ceased or was greatly reduced. As a consequence, large parts of the formerly submerged and unvegetated floodplains of these braided rivers dried out and were exposed to the wind. Because these floodplains consist of sediment containing a high content of glacially ground flour-like [[silt]] and [[clay]], they were highly susceptible to winnowing of their silts and [[clay]]s by the wind. Once entrained by the wind, particles were then deposited downwind. The loess deposits found along both sides of the [[Mississippi embayment|Mississippi River Alluvial Valley]] are a classic example of periglacial loess.<ref name=\"MuhsOthers2003a\">{{cite journal|last1=Bettis|first1=E.A.|last2=Muhs|first2=D.R.|last3=Roberts|first3=H.M.|last4=Wintle|first4=A.G.|title=Last Glacial loess in the conterminous USA|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|date=2003|volume=22|issue=18\u201319|pages=1907\u20131946|doi=10.1016/S0277-3791(03)00169-0|bibcode=2003QSRv...22.1907A}}</ref><ref name=\"esp.cr.usgs.gov\">{{cite journal|last1=Muhs|first1= D.R.|first2=E.A. |last2=Bettis, III|date=2003|url=http://esp.cr.usgs.gov/info/eolian/MuhsBettis2003GSAsp370.pdf |title=Quaternary loess-paleosol sequences as examples of climate-driven sedimentary extremes|journal=GSA Special Papers|volume=370|pages= 53\u201374|doi=10.1130/0-8137-2370-1.53|isbn= 9780813723709}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Quaternary]], loess and loess-like sediments were formed in periglacial environments on mid-continental [[Shield (geology)|shield]] areas in Europe and Siberia, on the margins of high mountain ranges like in [[Tajikistan]] and on semi-arid margins of some lowland deserts like in China.<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\"/>\n\nIn England, periglacial loess is also known as [[brickearth]].\n\n===Non-glacial===\nNon-glacial loess can originate from [[desert]]s, [[dune field]]s, [[playa lake]]s, and [[volcanic ash]].\n\nSome types of nonglacial loess are:<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Iriondo | first1 = M.H. | last2 = Krohling | first2 = D.M. | year = 2007 | title = Non-classical types of loess | journal = [[Sedimentary Geology (journal)|Sedimentary Geology]] | volume = 202 | issue = 3| pages = 352\u2013368 | bibcode=2007SedG..202..352I | doi=10.1016/j.sedgeo.2007.03.012}}</ref>\n* [[Desert]] loess produced by aeolian attrition of quartz grains <ref>Whalley, W.B., Marshall, J.R., Smith, B.J. 1982, Origin of desert loess from some experimental observations, Nature, 300, 433-435.</ref> \n* [[Volcanic]] loess in Ecuador and Argentina;\n* [[Tropical]] loess in Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay;\n* [[Gypsum]] loess in Spain;\n* [[Trade wind]] loess in Venezuela and Brazil;\n* [[Anticyclonic]] loess in Argentina.\n\nThe thick Chinese loess deposits are non-glacial loess having been blown in from deserts in northern China.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Ding | first1 = Z. | last2 = Sun | first2 = J. | year = 1999 | title = Changes in Sand Content of Loess Deposits along a North\u2013South Transect of the Chinese Loess Plateau and the Implications for Desert Variations. | url = | journal = [[Quaternary Research]] | volume = 52 | issue = 1| pages = 56\u201362 | doi=10.1006/qres.1999.2045| bibcode = 1999QuRes..52...56D }}</ref> The loess covering the [[Great Plains]] of [[Nebraska]], [[Kansas]], and [[Colorado]] is considered to be non-glacial desert loess.<ref name=\"MuhsOthers2003a\"/> Non-glacial desert loess is also found in Australia<ref>{{cite journal|last=Haberlah|first=D|year=2007|title=A call for Australian loess|journal=Area |volume=39 |issue=2|pages= 224\u2013229|doi=10.1111/j.1475-4762.2007.00730.x}}</ref> and Africa.<ref name=\"esp.cr.usgs.gov\"/>\n\n==Fertility==\nLoess tends to develop into very rich soils. Under appropriate climatic conditions, it is some of the most agriculturally productive terrain in the world.<ref>{{cite book|last=Getis|first=Arthur|author2=Judith Getis and Jerome D. Fellmann|title=Introduction to Geography, Seventh Edition|year=2000|publisher=[[McGraw Hill]]|isbn=0-697-38506-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/introductiontoge00geti/page/99 99]|url=https://archive.org/details/introductiontoge00geti/page/99}}</ref>\n\nSoils underlain by loess tend to be excessively drained. The fine grains [[weathering|weather]] rapidly due to their large surface area, making soils derived from loess rich.  One theory states that the fertility of loess soils is due largely to [[cation exchange capacity]] (the ability of plants to absorb nutrients from the soil) and [[porosity]] (the air-filled space in the soil). The fertility of loess is not due to organic matter content, which tends to be rather low, unlike tropical soils which derive their fertility almost wholly from organic matter.\n\nEven well managed loess [[arable land|farmland]] can experience dramatic [[erosion]] of well over 2.5&nbsp;kg /m<sup>2</sup> per year. In China the [[Loess Plateau|loess deposits]] which give the [[Yellow River]] its color have been farmed and have produced phenomenal yields for over one thousand years. Winds pick up loess particles, contributing to the [[Asian Dust]] pollution problem. The largest deposit of loess in the United States, the [[Loess Hills]] along the border of [[Iowa]] and Nebraska, has survived intensive farming and [[Land degradation|poor farming practices]]. For almost 150 years, this loess deposit was farmed with [[mouldboard plough]]s and fall tilled, both intensely erosive. At times it suffered erosion rates of over 10 kilograms per square meter per year. Today this loess deposit is worked as low till or [[no till]] in all areas and is aggressively [[terrace (agriculture)|terraced]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n==Large areas of loess deposits and soils==\n===Argentina===\n[[File:ArgentinaLoess.JPG|right|thumb|An [[outcrop]] of loess in [[Patagonia]]]]\nMuch of Argentina is covered by loess. Two areas of loess are usually distinguished in Argentina: the neotropical loess north of [[30th parallel south|latitude 30\u00b0 S]] and the pampean loess.<ref name=Sagayo/>\n\nThe neotropical loess is made of silt or silty clay. Relative to the pampean loess the neotropical loess is poor in [[quartz]] and [[calcium carbonate]]. The source region for this loess is thought by some scientists to be areas of [[fluvio-glacial]] deposits the Andean foothills formed by the [[Patagonian Ice Sheet]]. Other researchers stress the importance of [[tephra|volcanic material]] in the neotropical loess.<ref name=Sagayo/>\n\nThe pampean loess is sandy or made of silty sand.<ref name=Sagayo>{{cite journal |last=Sagayo |first=Jos\u00e9 Manuel |date=1995 |title=The Argentine neotropical loess: An overview |url= |journal=Quaternary Science Reviews |publisher=Pergamon |volume=14 |issue=7\u20138 |pages=755\u2013766 |doi=10.1016/0277-3791(95)00050-X |bibcode=1995QSRv...14..755S }}</ref>\n\n=== Central Asia ===\nFrom Southern Tajikistan up to Almaty, Kazakhstan, spans an area of multiple loess deposits.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ding |first=Z.L. |date=2002 |title=The loess record in southern Tajikistan and correlation with Chinese loess |url= |journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters |publisher=Elsevier |volume=200 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=387\u2013400|doi=10.1016/S0012-821X(02)00637-4 |bibcode=2002E&PSL.200..387D }}, Fig. 1 (b) showing the distribution of loess, deserts, and mountains in Central Asia (adopted from [T.S. Liu, Loess and the Environment, China Ocean Press, Beijing, 1985.]). The locality of the Chashmanigar loess section is indicated by the solid arrow.</ref>\n\n===China===\nThe [[Loess Plateau]] (simplified Chinese: \u9ec4\u571f\u9ad8\u539f; traditional Chinese: \u9ec3\u571f\u9ad8\u539f; pinyin: hu\u00e1ngt\u01d4 g\u0101oyu\u00e1n), also known as the Huangtu Plateau, is a [[plateau]] that covers an area of some 640,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> in the upper and middle of [[China]]'s [[Yellow River]] and China proper.  The Yellow River was so named because the loess forming its banks gave a yellowish tint to the water.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Huang He |url=http://www.bartleby.com/65/hu/HuangHe.html |encyclopedia=[[The Columbia Encyclopedia]] |edition=6th |year=2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605050404/http://www.bartleby.com/65/hu/HuangHe.html |archivedate=June 5, 2009 }}</ref> The soil of this region has been called the \"most highly erodible soil on earth\".<ref>John M. Laflen, Soil Erosion and Dryland Farming, 2000, CRC Press, 736 pages {{ISBN|0-8493-2349-5}}</ref> The Loess Plateau and its dusty [[soil]] cover almost all of [[Shanxi]], [[Shaanxi]], and [[Gansu]] provinces, the [[Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region]], and parts of others.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n===New Zealand===\nExtensive areas of loess occur in New Zealand including the [[Canterbury Plains]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/canterbury-region/page-3|title=Canterbury Region|publisher= Encyclopedia of New Zealand|author=John Wilson|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> and on the [[Banks Peninsula]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Eileen McSaveney|title= Glaciers and glaciation - Retreating ice and the glacier legacy|publisher= Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/photograph/10750/loess-deposits-banks-peninsula|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> <ref>Smalley, I.J., Davin, J.E. 1980. The First Hundred Years-A Historical Bibliography of New Zealand Loess. New Zealand Soil Bureau Bibliographic Report 28, 166pp.</ref> The basis of loess stratigraphy was introduced by [[John Hardcastle]] in 1890 <ref>*Hardcastle, J. 1890. On the Timaru loess as a climate register. Transcations & Proceedings of the New Zealand Institute 23, 324-332 (on line: Royal Society of New Zealand http://rsnz.natlib.govt.nz; reproduced in Loess Letter supplement 23, November 1988).</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[File:Distribution of loess in North America.gif|thumb|Map showing the distribution of loess in United States.<ref name=\"usgs muhs\">{{cite web |author= Muhs|title=Eolian History of North America: Task 2, Understand the paleoclimatic significance of loess |url= http://gec.cr.usgs.gov/archive/eolian/task2.shtml |publisher= [[USGS]] |date= 2013-02-06|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130218195902/http://gec.cr.usgs.gov/archive/eolian/task2.shtml |archive-date= 2013-02-18 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>]]\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2016}}\nThe [[Loess Hills]] of Iowa owe their fertility to the [[prairie]] [[topsoil]]s built by 10,000 years of post-glacial accumulation of organic-rich [[humus]] as a consequence of a persistent [[grassland]] [[biome]]. When the valuable [[A horizon|A-horizon]] topsoil is eroded or degraded, the underlying loess soil is infertile, and requires the addition of [[fertilizer]] in order to support [[agriculture]].\n\nThe loess along the [[Mississippi River]] near [[Vicksburg, Mississippi|Vicksburg]], [[Mississippi]], consist of three layers. The ''Peoria Loess'', ''Sicily Island Loess'', and ''Crowley's Ridge Loess'' accumulated at different periods of time during the [[Pleistocene]]. Ancient soils, called [[paleosol]]s, have developed in the top of the Sicily Island Loess and Crowley's Ridge Loess. The lowermost loess, the Crowley's Ridge Loess, accumulated during the late [[Illinoian (stage)|Illinoian Stage]]. The middle loess, Sicily Island Loess, accumulated during early [[Wisconsin glaciation|Wisconsin Stage]]. The uppermost loess, the Peoria Loess, in which the modern soil has developed, accumulated during the late Wisconsin Stage. Animal remains include terrestrial [[gastropod]]s and [[mastodon]]s.<ref name=\"MillerOthers1\">Miller, B.J., G.C. Lewis, J.J. Alford, and W.J. Day, 1985, [https://www.scribd.com/doc/18934817/1984-Louisiana-Loess-Fieldtrip-Guidebook ''Loesses in Louisiana and at Vicksburg, Mississippi. Guidebook, Friends of the Pleistocene Field Trip, 12-14 April, 1985.''] [[LA Agricultural Experimental Station]], [[Louisiana State University]], [[Baton Rouge]], [[Louisiana]]. 126 pp.</ref>\n\n=== Europe ===\nLoess deposits of varying thickness (decimeter to several tens of meters) are widely distributed over the European continent.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Schaetzl|first=Randall J.|last2=Bettis|first2=E. Arthur|last3=Crouvi|first3=Onn|last4=Fitzsimmons|first4=Kathryn E.|last5=Grimley|first5=David A.|last6=Hambach|first6=Ulrich|last7=Lehmkuhl|first7=Frank|last8=Markovi\u0107|first8=Slobodan B.|last9=Mason|first9=Joseph A.|last10=Owczarek|first10=Piotr|last11=Roberts|first11=Helen M.|date=May 2018|title=Approaches and challenges to the study of loess\u2014Introduction to the LoessFest Special Issue|journal=Quaternary Research|volume=89|issue=3|pages=563\u2013618|doi=10.1017/qua.2018.15|issn=0033-5894|bibcode=2018QuRes..89..563S|doi-access=free}}</ref> The northern European loess belt stretches fromsouthern England and northern [[France]] to [[Germany]], [[Poland]] and the southern [[Ukraine]] and deposits are characterized by strong influences of [[periglacial]] conditions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vandenberghe|first=Jef|last2=French|first2=Hugh M.|last3=Gorbunov|first3=Aldar|last4=Marchenko|first4=Sergei|last5=Velichko|first5=Andrey A.|last6=Jin|first6=Huijun|last7=Cui|first7=Zhijiu|last8=Zhang|first8=Tingjun|last9=Wan|first9=Xudong|date=2014|title=The Last Permafrost Maximum (LPM) map of the Northern Hemisphere: permafrost extent and mean annual air temperatures, 25\u201317 ka BP|journal=Boreas|volume=43|issue=3|pages=652\u2013666|doi=10.1111/bor.12070|issn=1502-3885}}</ref> South-eastern European loess is mainly deposited in plateau-like situations in the [[Danube basin]]s, likely derived from the Danube River system.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fitzsimmons|first=Kathryn E.|last2=Markovi\u0107|first2=Slobodan B.|last3=Hambach|first3=Ulrich|date=2012-05-18|title=Pleistocene environmental dynamics recorded in the loess of the middle and lower Danube basin|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|volume=41|pages=104\u2013118|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2012.03.002|issn=0277-3791|bibcode=2012QSRv...41..104F}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jipa|first=Dan C.|date=November 2014|title=The conceptual sedimentary model of the Lower Danube loess basin: Sedimentogenetic implications|journal=Quaternary International|volume=351|pages=14\u201324|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2013.06.008|issn=1040-6182|bibcode=2014QuInt.351...14J}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00dajv\u00e1ri|first=G\u00e1bor|last2=Varga|first2=Andrea|last3=Ramos|first3=Frank C.|last4=Kov\u00e1cs|first4=J\u00e1nos|last5=N\u00e9meth|first5=Tibor|last6=Stevens|first6=Thomas|date=April 2012|title=Evaluating the use of clay mineralogy, Sr\u2013Nd isotopes and zircon U\u2013Pb ages in tracking dust provenance: An example from loess of the Carpathian Basin|journal=Chemical Geology|volume=304-305|pages=83\u201396|doi=10.1016/j.chemgeo.2012.02.007|issn=0009-2541|bibcode=2012ChGeo.304...83U}}</ref> In south-western Europe, relocated loess derivatives are mostly restricted to the [[Ebro Valley]] and central [[Spain]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boixadera|first=Jaume|last2=Poch|first2=Rosa M.|last3=Lowick|first3=Sally E.|last4=Balasch|first4=J. Carles|date=July 2015|title=Loess and soils in the eastern Ebro Basin|journal=Quaternary International|volume=376|pages=114\u2013133|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2014.07.046|issn=1040-6182|bibcode=2015QuInt.376..114B}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bertran|first=Pascal|last2=Liard|first2=Morgane|last3=Sitzia|first3=Luca|last4=Tissoux|first4=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|date=November 2016|title=A map of Pleistocene aeolian deposits in Western Europe, with special emphasis on France|journal=Journal of Quaternary Science|volume=31|issue=8|pages=e2909|doi=10.1002/jqs.2909|issn=0267-8179|bibcode=2016JQS....31E2909B}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{annotated link|B\u00f6rde}} \u2013 North German loess regions\n* {{annotated link|G\u00e4u|G\u00e4ue}} \u2013 South German loess regions\n* {{annotated link|Loam}}\n\n==References==\nThis article incorporates CC-BY-3.0 text from the reference<ref name=\"Frechen 2011\">{{cite journal | last1 = Frechen | first1 = M | year = 2011 | title = Loess in Europe | url = | journal = Quaternary Science Journal | volume = 60 | issue = 1| pages = 3\u20135 | doi = 10.3285/eg.60.1.00 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Smalley, I. J. (editor) 1975. ''Loess Lithology & Genesis''. Benchmark Geology 26. Dowden, Hutchinson & Ross 454pp.\n* Smalley, I. J. 1980.  ''Loess: A Partial Bibliography''.  Geobooks/Elsevier. {{ISBN|0 86094 036 5}}. 103pp.\n* Rozycki, S. Z. 1991. ''Loess and Loess-like Deposits''. Ossolineum Wroclaw {{ISBN|83-04-03745-9}}. 187pp.\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|loess}}\n{{commons category|Loess}}\n{{Americana Poster}}\n* 2006, [http://www.semp.us/publications/biot_printview.php?BiotID=357 ''The Secret of China\u2019s Vast Loess Plateau''] [[Suburban Emergency Management Project]], Chicago, Illinois.\n* 2007, [http://www.ufz.de/index.php?en=15536 ''New European Loess Map.''] [[Helmholtz Centre for Environmental Research]], [[Leipzig]], Germany.\n* [http://www.museum.state.il.us/exhibits/larson/loess.html ''Glacial Deposits: Loess and Till.''] [[Illinois State Museum]], [[Springfield, Illinois]].\n* Briedis. C.A., 2006, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080905190943/http://www.isgs.uiuc.edu/sections/quat/loessthick-map.shtml ''Loess Thickness Map (of Illinois).''] [[Illinois State Geological Survey]], [[Champaign, Illinois]].\n* [https://www.lbk.ars.usda.gov/wewc/biblio/bar.htm The Bibliography of Aeolian Research]\n* Heinrich, P.V., 2008, [https://web.archive.org/web/20090325233831/http://www.lgs.lsu.edu/deploy/uploads/Loess%20Map%20of%20LA.pdf ''Loess map of Louisiana.''], Public Information Series. no. 12, [[Louisiana Geological Survey]], [[Baton Rouge]], [[Louisiana]].\n* Prior, J.C., and D.J. Quade, nd, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080521133019/http://www.igsb.uiowa.edu/browse/loess/loess.htm ''The Loess Hills: A Geologic View.''] [[Iowa Geological Survey]], [[Iowa Department of Natural Resources|Department of Natural Resources]], [[Iowa City]], Iowa.\n* [[U.S. Geological Survey]], 1999, [http://pubs.usgs.gov/info/loess/ ''Geology of the Loess Hills, Iowa'']\n* [[U.S. Geological Survey]], 2006, [http://esp.cr.usgs.gov/info/